252cec85-7677-486c-ae33-fa1a8565016b	ContextAttributor	To enhance the interpretability and trustworthiness of generative QA systems through efficient context attribution, leveraging combinatorial multi-armed bandit optimization techniques.	Existing context attribution methods are often computationally expensive and may lack interpretability and efficiency, particularly for lengthy contexts. Traditional methods, such as perturbation techniques, require extensive queries which can be impractical in real-world applications, leading to difficulties in identifying the specific context contributions to model outputs.	Application of context attribution in generative question-answering systems that utilize large language models. Implementation of a combinatorial multi-armed bandit approach to improve efficiency and accuracy in attributing context segments to the output responses.	["AI developers","Researchers in NLP and machine learning","Companies developing AI-driven QA systems","Educational institutions focused on AI ethics","Businesses needing AI transparency"]	The system treats each context segment as an arm in a multi-armed bandit framework. It uses Combinatorial Thompson Sampling (CTS) to explore the optimal subsets of context segments with minimized queries. The system dynamically adapts based on prior outcomes, measuring the supportiveness of each segment through a custom reward function based on normalized token likelihoods, which captures the relevance of context segments to the generated response.	Front-End Interface: User inputs questions and context. Backend Processor: Manages model selection and queries using LLMs. Context Attribution Module: Implements CTS to explore context segments and compute their contributions. Reward Function: Evaluates the effectiveness of segment subsets using normalized token likelihoods. Reporting Module: Provides attributions and insights in a user-friendly format.	The application of Combinatorial Thompson Sampling for efficient and adaptive exploration of context segments significantly reduces computational overhead while maintaining high attribution fidelity. This is in contrast to traditional methods that often require exhaustive sampling. The use of normalized token likelihoods as a reward function improves the precision of segment importance evaluations.	Facilitating real-time context attribution for generative AI systems in industries such as customer support, legal query responses, and educational platforms, enabling users to understand which parts of a context led to certain outputs.	\N	2025-06-26 04:00:00+00	2025-06-26 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.19977", "title": "ContextAttributor"}]	{"University of Notre Dame","IBM Research","Data Science teams in academic institutions"}
