e2f37a28-b91a-4d7a-8e54-2db4a6a405b8	WyckoffDiff	Revolutionize materials discovery by generating crystals with precise symmetry characteristics using a generative diffusion model.	Existing generative models for crystal structures often fail to account for symmetry, leading to unrealistic material predictions that diverge from actual crystalline properties. These models typically do not utilize spaces of potential high-symmetry materials, resulting in inefficient exploration and generation processes.	Generation of symmetric crystal structures using a novel generative diffusion model. Development of protostructures that reflect more realistic materials for applications in materials science and engineering. Fast generation of materials without exact geometry, streamlining the materials discovery workflow.	["Materials scientists and researchers","Chemical and materials engineering companies","Industries focused on materials innovation","Academic institutions and research labs","Manufacturers requiring advanced materials for production processes"]	The model generates crystal structures by sampling from distributions that respect symmetry constraints defined by Wyckoff positions. It utilizes a discrete diffusion mechanism to iteratively refine random initial configurations into valid crystal structures while ensuring they adhere to symmetry rules. The neural architecture, WyckoffGNN, processes these configurations as a fully connected graph, enabling efficient learning and generation of new materials.	The architecture comprises input layers for space group sampling, a graph-based representation of Wyckoff positions processing through message-passing neural networks (GNN) and an output layer producing probability distributions for element placements. The discrete diffusion model is structured to handle categorical variables, focusing on generating valid material prototypes without full geometrical resolutions until necessary. Optimization techniques include loss functions 