2014a648-5ec5-420c-925b-c690929e2fdf	Stochastic Growth Automata Toolkit (SGAT)	Empower researchers and organizations to accurately model and simulate biological growth patterns and self-organizing processes using stochastic neural cellular automata.	Current modeling techniques struggle with the intricacies of biological processes that exhibit stochastic behavior. Traditional deterministic models lack the flexibility needed to replicate the randomness found in nature, leading to oversimplified interpretations. Addressing these limitations is essential for accurate modeling of phenomena like tissue growth and differentiation.	Development of a toolkit for modeling self-organizing biological processes, focusing on tissue growth simulations, image morphogenesis, and microscopy image segmentation. The toolkit will include components for integrating intrinsic noise with neural cellular automata models.	["Research laboratories in biology","Biotech companies focusing on tissue engineering","Pharmaceutical companies involved in drug testing","Academic institutions in life sciences","Healthcare organizations studying cancer growth dynamics"]	The system allows users to define the initial conditions of cellular simulations based on real or synthetic data. It incorporates multiple neural cellular automata operating under different local update rules with stochastic inputs. The simulation updates occur over time steps, where each cell's future state is determined probabilistically, balancing local interactions with global dynamics.	1. Input Layer: Configuration settings and initial cellular states. 2. Mixture of Neural Cellular Automata: A core framework allowing for multiple distinct automata with associated noise models. 3. Probabilistic Rule Selector: Uses a neural network to determine the active automaton for each cell based on local information. 4. Simulation Module: Runs the evolution of cell states and interactions across discrete time steps. 5. Output Reporting Module: Provides visualizations of cellular dynamics and metrics like cell type distribution.	The introduction of a mixed probabilistic regime in neural cellular automata allows the simulation of complex biological behaviors with a level of fidelity not seen in traditional models. The toolkit also includes interpretable rule assignments for better understanding of cellular dynamics and emergent behaviors.	Researchers can utilize SGAT to model the nuanced dynamics of stem cell differentiation and observe how within-cell heterogeneity affects tissue patterning. The toolkit can also be used to analyze image data for unsupervised segmentation of cell types in microscopy images.	\N	2025-06-26 04:00:00+00	2025-06-26 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.20486", "title": "Stochastic Growth Automata Toolkit (SGAT)"}]	{"Fondazione Human Technople","University of Trieste"}
08964c3f-cef3-415c-8287-f388358bfc67	Decrypto Reasoning Benchmark	Evaluate and improve the theory of mind and multi-agent reasoning capabilities of large language models through an interactive game setting.	Current evaluations of multi-agent reasoning in AI fail to analyze agents' understanding of mental states, leading to inadequate training and capabilities. Existing benchmarks lack interactivity and robustness, creating a gap in assessing theory of mind (ToM) in AI agents.	The benchmark is designed for evaluating AI models on theory of mind in interactive multi-agent tasks, allowing the study of cooperation and competition in strategic communication games.	["AI researchers","Cognitive scientists","Data scientists","Software engineers in AI development","Multi-agent system developers"]	The Decrypto game involves three players: the Encoder (Alice), the Decoder (Bob), and the Interceptor (Eve). The Encoder gives hints for a code composed of numbers that correspond to keywords. The game’s outcome relies on the collaborative efforts of Alice and Bob against Eve, who tries to intercept the code based on the provided hints and history. It fosters a complex reasoning environment where AI must model and predict others' mental states.	The system comprises three agents (Alice, Bob, Eve), with roles managed through a game state tracker that maintains histories of hints and codes. The interactions follow a turn-based structure where players alternate taking actions and receiving feedback for their choices, enabling data collection on reasoning patterns.	Decrypto uniquely combines interactive gameplay with theory of mind evaluation, offering a versatile platform for benchmarking AI agents' reasoning capabilities. It eliminates confounding factors present in traditional tests and allows researchers to design custom experiments through simple prompt adjustments.	AI evaluation for multi-agent scenarios where understanding and predicting the actions of other agents is critical. Decrypto can be applied in testing models intended for social robotics, negotiation systems, and cooperative AI applications.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e4/Arms_of_University_of_Oxford.svg/500px-Arms_of_University_of_Oxford.svg.png	2025-06-26 04:00:00+00	2025-06-26 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.20664", "title": "Decrypto Reasoning Benchmark"}]	{"Meta AI Research","University of Oxford"}
