e0911197-7467-44e2-87cf-940c6b012824	DualEquiNet	To enhance the modeling of large biomolecules like RNA and proteins by integrating dual-space representations that capture both local atomic interactions and long-range structural dependencies.	Existing methods struggle to effectively model large biomolecules due to limitations in capturing hierarchical structures and long-range dependencies. Most current approaches either oversimplify the molecular representation or require excessive computational resources, limiting their scalability and efficacy.	Multi-scale modeling of large biomolecules through the integration of Euclidean and spherical harmonics representations. Applications in RNA and protein property prediction as well as in structure-based drug discovery.	["Biochemists and molecular biologists","Pharmaceutical companies","Academic researchers in computational biology","Bioinformatics firms","Drug design and development teams"]	DualEquiNet constructs node representations in both Euclidean and spherical harmonics spaces, facilitating effective message passing and pooling operations that integrate local and global geometric contexts. The model implements a Cross-Space Interaction Pooling mechanism to enable hierarchical aggregation from atom-level to residue-level features, suitable for large biomolecular structures.	The architecture consists of dual-space representations with a series of DualEqui layers followed by a Cross-Space Interaction Pooling module. The model allows for both within-space and cross-space message passing, updating features based on local neighbor proximity and long-range structural similarity. Residue-level features are computed through aggregation of atomic features.	Introduction of the DualEquiNet architecture that effectively combines Euclidean space local interactions with spherical harmonics global relationships, allowing for efficient long-range information flow. The Cross-Space Interaction Pooling mechanism optimally integrates these two spaces for biologically meaningful feature aggregation.	Optimizing RNA stability predictions for mRNA vaccines, predicting protein structures, and estimating solvent-accessible surfaces from 3D models.	\N	2025-06-26 04:00:00+00	2025-06-26 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.19862", "title": "DualEquiNet"}]	{"The Pennsylvania State University","Independent Researchers"}
210e9cdb-a6e7-4de7-926b-388100c08451	MNN-AECS	To enhance energy efficiency in on-device Large Language Model (LLM) decoding through adaptive core selection without compromising decoding speed.	LLM decoding on mobile devices consumes excessive energy due to memory-boundedness, resulting in rapid battery depletion and increased CPU heat, thereby negatively impacting user experience and device longevity.	Optimizing the decoding phase of LLM inference on Android and iOS devices using an adaptive selection of CPU cores, targeting a reduction in energy consumption while maintaining acceptable decoding speed.	["Mobile app developers integrating LLMs","Mobile device manufacturers","Researchers in AI and mobile computing","Consumer electronics users seeking efficient AI solutions"]	MNN-AECS evaluates and selects the optimal low-power CPU cores for decoding tasks dynamically based on real-time performance metrics and energy consumption, executing LLM processes in a way that minimizes battery usage without a significant drop in decoding speed.	MNN-AECS consists of a core adaptive energy-centric selection algorithm integrated into the MNN inference engine, which interfaces with the mobile OS to control CPU core affinities and threading parameters, enabling real-time adjustments during LLM decoding tasks.	The use of Adaptive Energy-Centric Core Selection (AECS) enables efficient core utilization during LLM decoding while preserving speed, making the engine capable of running on lower-powered cores, which has not been implemented previously in LLM inference engines for mobile devices.	Deployment in mobile applications for real-time language processing tasks, such as chatbots or virtual assistants, that require efficient power consumption and quick responses.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/d/da/Sjtu-logo-standard-red.png/300px-Sjtu-logo-standard-red.png	2025-06-26 04:00:00+00	2025-06-26 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.19884", "title": "MNN-AECS"}]