2b51b82d-cc1f-4c41-b238-a4059042e85c	Causal-Aware QoE Optimizer for VR	Enhance the Quality of Experience (QoE) in multi-user VR environments by intelligently optimizing resource allocation through adaptive keyframe extraction and causal reinforcement learning.	Current VR interactions struggle with balancing low latency, high fidelity, and user satisfaction simultaneously. Traditional approaches often overlook the causal relationships between allocated bandwidth, CPU usage, and user perception, leading to inefficient resource utilization and suboptimal user experiences.	Multi-user virtual reality applications requiring real-time interaction, focusing on optimizing data transmission for motion synchronization and rendering using adaptive keyframe extraction techniques.	["Game developers","VR content creators","Telecommunications companies","VR hardware manufacturers","Research institutions studying VR experiences"]	The system utilizes motion capture data to create keyframes that represent significant user movements. Leveraging causal reinforcement learning, it dynamically adjusts keyframe ratios and resource allocations (bandwidth and CPU frequency) to enhance QoE by minimizing latency and maximizing fidelity based on user attention in the virtual environment.	The system consists of a central server that processes motion capture data, a causal inference network to analyze the impact of actions on user states, and a real-time optimized communication module to deliver data to users while minimizing lag and ensuring synchronization. A mixed-integer programming framework guides resource allocation decisions.	Integrating causal inference with reinforcement learning (PS-CDDPG) to facilitate more informed decision-making about resource allocation in real-time. The adaptive keyframe extraction process reduces bandwidth usage while maintaining high QoE through awareness of user attention.	The optimizer can be applied in various scenarios such as VR gaming, virtual meetings, and collaborative VR environments where interactive user experience is critical, significantly lowering latency and enhancing overall satisfaction.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/b/bb/Carnegie_Mellon_University_seal.svg/300px-Carnegie_Mellon_University_seal.svg.png	2025-06-26 04:00:00+00	2025-06-26 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.19890", "title": "Causal-Aware QoE Optimizer for VR"}]	{"The Hong Kong University of Science and Technology","Carnegie Mellon University","Stanford University","Research teams from participating telecommunications companies"}
5caa2a3b-9356-4f39-8456-b060fc492e31	BlockAI Energy Secure	To create a secure, intelligent, and efficient framework for energy transactions in the decentralized US energy market by integrating blockchain technology with AI-driven fraud detection.	The decentralized energy market faces challenges such as fraud, security vulnerabilities, and market instability. Traditional systems rely heavily on centralized structures, which are prone to manipulation, inefficiency, and do not offer real-time detection of fraudulent activities, leading to significant financial losses.	Deploying a secure, blockchain-based platform for peer-to-peer energy trading, integrating AI models for real-time fraud detection and market analysis. This includes utilizing smart contracts to ensure transparency and immutability of transactions.	["Energy producers (prosumers)","Consumers of energy","Electric utility companies","Blockchain technology developers","AI and machine learning consultants"]	The system operates on a two-layer architecture; the blockchain layer records energy transactions securely and immutably through smart contracts, while the AI layer conducts real-time analysis of transaction data to detect fraud. This includes streaming transaction details to machine learning models which analyze patterns to identify anomalies in energy trading behavior. Alerts are generated for suspicious activities, halting transactions until reviewed.	The framework integrates an Ethereum blockchain layer for recording transactions and a Python-based AI layer connected via APIs and oracles. Smart contracts enforce transaction rules, while the AI engine processes historical and current transaction data using machine learning algorithms, including Random Forest, Logistic Regression, and XG-Boost, for anomaly detection and market forecasting.	Hybrid integration of blockchain and AI systems for real-time fraud detection addresses the limitations of traditional energy markets. The use of machine learning algorithms on transaction data enables proactive mitigation of fraudulent activities. This system enhances transparency and market stability by predicting energy demand and price fluctuations.	Energy producers can securely trade excess energy with consumers using the platform, which ensures tracked and fraud-free transactions. AI-driven analytical tools provide market players with insights for price predictions and inventory management, enhancing the efficiency of energy resource allocation.	\N	2025-06-26 04:00:00+00	2025-06-26 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.19870", "title": "BlockAI Energy Secure"}]	{"Md Asif Ul Hoq Khan","MD Zahedul Islam","Istiaq Ahmed","Md Masud Karim Rabbi","Farhana Rahman Anonna","MD Abdul Fahim Zeeshan","Mehedi Hasan Ridoy","Bivash Ranjan Chowdhury","Md Nazmul Shakir Rabbi","GM Alamin Sadnan"}
8b29905b-8c0b-4d4e-9833-ec93e796d1fc	CardioAlign AI	Enhance non-invasive cardiac diagnostics by integrating electrocardiograms (ECG) with cardiac magnetic resonance (CMR) imaging data using a multimodal contrastive learning framework.	Current methods of assessing cardiac function often rely solely on ECG or CMR separately, leading to limited information. ECG provides electrical activity data, while CMR offers structural and functional insights but is costly and less accessible. The combination of these modalities can bridge this gap and improve diagnostic capabilities.	Integration of ECG and CMR data for improved assessment of cardiac function, enabling better diagnosis and management of cardiovascular diseases through patient and temporal alignment.	["Healthcare providers","Cardiology departments","Medical imaging facilities","Research institutions focused on cardiovascular health"]	CardioAlign AI uses a two-step approach. First, it pre-trains individual models for ECG and CMR using masked autoencoders to capture relevant features. Second, it applies a contrastive learning framework, combining global and local alignment strategies to match ECG segments with corresponding CMR frames. The model outputs enriched ECG representations capturing insights from both modalities.	The system consists of separate encoders for ECG and CMR, each equipped with transformer-based architectures. The ECG encoder processes multi-lead time-series data while the CMR encoder handles short-axis image sequences. Global and local contrastive losses are applied during training to ensure alignment, enhancing cross-modal representations.	The introduction of a novel contrastive learning framework that captures both global patient-level and fine-grained temporal relationships between ECG and CMR embeddings without the need for additional learnable parameters, improving diagnostic accuracy and efficiency.	Improved retrieval of patients with similar cardiac phenotypes and predicting important cardiac function parameters such as ventricular volumes and ejection fraction using enriched ECG data.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/Logo_of_the_Technical_University_of_Munich.svg/360px-Logo_of_the_Technical_University_of_Munich.svg.png	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.20683", "title": "CardioAlign AI"}]	{"Technical University of Munich (TUM)","Imperial College London","UK Biobank Research Group"}
66f0ff89-c0e7-43d5-8dae-11841f2a1028	PruneForget	Enable efficient and rapid class unlearning in machine learning models while maintaining high predictive accuracy and ensuring compliance with privacy regulations.	Current methods for machine unlearning are slow and require extensive computational resources, or they affect the predictive accuracy of the retained classes. Existing solutions often treat unlearning as a separate process from inference, which complicates deployment in latency-sensitive applications.	Class unlearning for deep neural networks deployed in Machine Learning as a Service (MLaaS) settings, enabling compliance with privacy requests while preserving model performance.	["MLaaS providers","Data privacy officers","Companies handling sensitive data","AI developers","Regulatory compliance teams"]	The system applies orthogonal convolutional kernel regularization combined with dynamic soft pruning to quickly suppress class-specific filters in neural networks. This process ensures defined feature separation, allowing for rapid forgetting of data associated with specific classes while retaining the model's performance on other classes.	Composed of an Input Layer, Orthogonal Regularization Module, Class-Specific Filter Selector, Dynamic Soft Pruning Module, Prediction Stream, and Reporting Module, all optimized for integration in MLaaS environments with low-latency responses.	Combining orthogonal regularization with soft pruning enables fast, efficient class unlearning without the overhead of full model retraining or resource-intensive methods. This allows for millisecond-level execution speeds and effectively balances retention of accuracy with privacy compliance.	Enabling organizations to respond to data deletion requests in real-time without the need to retrain models, ensuring compliance with regulations such as GDPR and CCPA while maintaining operational efficiency.	\N	2025-06-26 04:00:00+00	2025-06-26 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.19891", "title": "PruneForget"}]	{"Southwest Jiaotong University"}
8474871a-a46e-4c1c-bcbd-dc6b11489bc3	FlightKooba	To provide a fast and interpretable model for flight trajectory prediction by leveraging the Koopman theory, HIPPO method, and state space equations.	Current flight trajectory prediction models often suffer from inefficiencies in training time and memory usage, as well as lack interpretability. The search for a method that balances computational efficiency with understandable outcomes is crucial for applications in air traffic management and flight safety.	Development of a predictive modeling framework specifically tailored for flight trajectory predictions that ensures both speed and interpretability. The framework will be adaptable to various time series forecasting scenarios beyond aviation.	["Aviation industry professionals","Air traffic controllers","Flight training institutions","Aerospace engineers","Researchers in dynamic systems"]	FlightKooba utilizes the HIPPO method to derive state space representations, facilitating the computation of Koopman operators directly from data. This results in a significant reduction in trainable parameters and improved interpretability. Predictions are made by inputting flight data to generate future trajectory states, while leveraging polynomial approximations for accuracy.	The system architecture consists of multiple modules: a HIPPO module for coefficient calculation, a Koopman operator computation block, and state space equation links. The model employs matrices to represent control inputs and state transitions, all optimized for minimal computation time.	FlightKooba introduces a novel combination of the HIPPO method with Koopman theory to create a fast, interpretable framework for predicting flight trajectories. This approach significantly reduces the number of parameters and training time compared to traditional deep learning methods.	FlightKooba can be utilized in real-time flight trajectory predictions to enhance pilot training, improve air traffic monitoring, and assist in safety assessments by identifying risky behavior patterns in flight data.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/6a/Nanjing_University_Logo.svg/260px-Nanjing_University_Logo.svg.png	2025-06-26 04:00:00+00	2025-06-26 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.19885", "title": "FlightKooba"}]	{"School of Computer Science, Civil Aviation Flight University of China","College of Computer Science, Nanjing University of Aeronautics and Astronautics"}
927ff513-7bd1-4ef9-9115-7c084da0674e	SpeakerTrack AI	Enhance the tracking accuracy and continuity of intermittent and moving speakers in audio environments through the integration of speaker embeddings with traditional tracking methods.		Improved speaker tracking in audio processing applications including real-time communication, automatic speech recognition, and audio enhancement systems. Integration with existing tracking systems to provide post-tracking identity reassignment using speaker embeddings.	["Audio processing companies","Speech recognition platforms","Conference systems providers","Telecommunication services","Research institutions in audio and speech technology"]	The system first tracks speakers using traditional methods, providing initial trajectories based on their Direction of Arrival (DoA). To improve identity assignment, speaker embeddings are extracted from enhanced audio signals using beamforming techniques that focus on speaker positions. These embeddings are compared with a pool of previously enrolled speaker identities to accurately reassign identities to track segments, correcting errors especially during inactivity periods.	Input Layer: Multichannel audio input; Beamforming Module: Enhances audio signals based on DoA information; Tracking Module: Initial identification and trajectory segmentation; Embedding Extraction: Uses a pretrained neural network model to obtain speaker embeddings; Identity Reassignment Module: Matches segment embeddings with enrollment pool to reassign identities based on similarity scores; Output Module: Provides corrected track identities and reports.	The integration of speaker embeddings for identity reassignment enhances conventional tracking methods, enabling them to maintain accuracy even with intermittent speakers. Improved robustness against overlapping voices through advanced beamforming techniques and customized embedding extraction periods contribute to performance.	Conferences where multiple speakers may change positions and become inactive. Telecommunication applications requiring accurate speaker identification during calls or video conferences despite active speaker movements. Research studies in audio analysis collecting data from dynamic speaking scenarios.	\N	2025-06-26 04:00:00+00	2025-06-26 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.19875", "title": "SpeakerTrack AI"}]	{"Orange Innovation, France","University de Lorraine, CNRS, Inria, Loria, France"}
190ce5bd-44d4-4c94-821f-603c018455f5	STIMULUS	To enhance the efficiency of multi-objective optimization methods by achieving fast convergence and reducing sample complexity for various machine learning tasks.	Existing multi-objective optimization algorithms often struggle with slow convergence rates and high sample complexity, making them inefficient for real-world applications. The need for a robust and scalable solution in dynamic scenarios where multiple conflicting objectives are present is critical.	Development of a family of algorithms (STIMULUS, STIMULUS-M, STIMULUS+, STIMULUS-M+) aimed at solving multi-objective optimization problems in both non-convex and strongly convex settings. These algorithms can be adapted for various applications in machine learning that require optimization across multiple objectives.	["Machine Learning practitioners and researchers","Data scientists in various industries such as finance, healthcare, and engineering","Developers of optimization tools and libraries","Organizations looking for efficient solutions for multi-objective decision-making"]	STIMULUS algorithms utilize variance-reduction techniques to estimate gradients in multi-objective settings, allowing for updates in a more efficient manner. They offer a double-loop structure where periodic evaluations of full multi-gradients are reduced and a stochastic multi-gradient estimator is used in the interim updates. Enhanced variants incorporate momentum terms and adaptive batching to further accelerate convergence.	The basic STIMULUS algorithm consists of an outer loop iterating through the gradient evaluation sections and an inner loop responsible for estimating gradients. Key components include: gradient calculation via recursive estimators, update rules dictated by convex combinations of gradients, and conditions for momentum adjustments and adaptive sampling.	Key innovations include the introduction of a variance-reduced stochastic multi-gradient estimation for improved convergence rates, the integration of momentum terms in STIMULUS-M for faster convergence, and adaptive batching techniques in STIMULUS+ and STIMULUS-M+ that minimize computational load while maintaining performance.	Applicable in settings such as multi-label learning, multi-task learning for recommendation systems, and decision-making scenarios where multiple criteria must be considered simultaneously. Demonstrated effectiveness in scenarios like ranking products or optimally allocating resources across multiple objectives.	\N	2025-06-26 04:00:00+00	2025-06-26 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.19883", "title": "STIMULUS"}]	{"University of North Texas",Amazon,"Rochester Institute of Technology","The Ohio State University"}
13ed301d-78ef-4825-a33c-56b30927f151	RCG-Defender	Provide a covert defense mechanism against privacy violation attacks on large language models through retrieval-confused generation techniques.	Large language models can infer sensitive personal attributes from seemingly benign user inputs, exposing individuals to privacy violation attacks. Existing defenses rely heavily on inefficient anonymization techniques and can be bypassed, highlighting the need for a time-efficient and covert defense strategy.	Defense against privacy violation attacks, specifically using the retrieval-confused generation method to respond to attacks with incorrect personal data while maintaining the normal operation of the model.	["AI security companies","Developers of large language model applications","Organizations concerned with data privacy"]	The RCG-Defender constructs a disturbed database by modifying user comments associated with personal attributes using a paraphrasing prompt. During the retrieval phase, the system retrieves the most irrelevant information from this disturbed database to replace sensitive content in attack queries, thus misleading attackers with incorrect personal attributes.	The architecture consists of two main stages: 1) Disturbed database construction using paraphrasing prompts to alter sensitive user comments, and 2) Confused retrieval that uses an irrelevant retrieval strategy to select comments from the disturbed database to replace the original user inputs.	The RCG-Defender employs a unique strategy of retrieval-confused generation, contrasting with existing defense methods by not rejecting the query but rather providing a deceptive response, thus concealing its defense mechanism from attackers.	Protection of user data from privacy violations in applications utilizing large language models, including customer service bots, social media analysis tools, and personal assistant technologies.	\N	2025-06-26 04:00:00+00	2025-06-26 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.19889", "title": "RCG-Defender"}]	{"Wanli Peng","Xin Chen","Hang Fu","Xinyu He","Yiming Xue","Juan Wen"}
f18d504c-f81c-4bfd-bcb9-80eb6177309d	RepuNet	Enhance the security and performance of decentralized federated learning (DFL) by implementing a dynamic reputation system that detects and mitigates malicious client behavior.	In decentralized federated learning, nodes have autonomy in model training and aggregation, which opens up vulnerabilities such as model poisoning, communication delays, and flooding attacks. Existing solutions often introduce heavy computational overhead and scalability issues, thus a more efficient method to assess node behavior is needed.	Dynamic reputation evaluation of nodes in decentralized federated learning environments. Monitoring for threats during model training and adjusting influence in model aggregation accordingly.	["Research institutions focusing on AI and machine learning","Organizations implementing federated learning systems","Cybersecurity firms","Developers of decentralized applications"]	RepuNet evaluates the behavior of nodes using observable metrics like model similarity, parameter changes, message latency, and communication volume. It scores node reputations dynamically and adjusts their influence in model aggregation accordingly, leading to the exclusion of malicious contributions.	RepuNet operates as a modular component integrated into the Nebula platform, where it interacts with nodes during each training round to evaluate and update reputations based on specified metrics.	RepuNet employs a decentralized and adaptive reputation mechanism that dynamically updates scores and allows for the gradual exclusion and reintegration of nodes based on their performance. This is achieved without the overhead associated with blockchain and centralized filtering mechanisms.	RepuNet can be utilized in various settings, such as facilitating safer and more reliable federated learning experiments among collaborative nodes, where nodes can trust the integrity of model contributions while preserving autonomy in training.	\N	2025-06-26 04:00