ancing data-driven decision-making in transportation infrastructure planning and congestion management.	\N	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2411.02136", "title": "DroneTrax"}]	{"EPFL, Switzerland","KAIST, South Korea"}
81b731d2-f668-4899-86a0-ccf92a7a8fdd	Recall and Refine Domain Adaptation (RRDA)	To provide an efficient framework for Source-free Open-set Domain Adaptation (SF-OSDA) that enhances the classification of known and unknown classes without the need for labeled source data, addressing both distribution and label shifts effectively.	Existing SF-OSDA approaches suffer from performance degradation when encountering novel classes not represented in the source domain, often relying on thresholding to classify unknowns, leading to inaccurate predictions and a lack of discriminative feature learning for these unknown classes.	Adaptation of pre-trained models to classify unlabeled target domain samples that may contain known and unknown classes. Integration of additional features generated from synthetic data to improve model performance.	["Machine Learning Researchers","Data Scientists","AI Practitioners","Technology Firms focusing on Computer Vision","Industries dealing with Privacy-sensitive Data"]	RRDA operates in two stages: First, it generates synthetic features representing both known and unknown classes through optimized entropy techniques. Second, it trains a new target classifier using these synthetic features, followed by adapting the entire model to the target domain using any source-free adaptation method.	RRDA consists of three main components: 1) Generating synthetic features through optimization based on known and unknown classes. 2) A target classifier that is trained on these synthetic features and can classify both known and unknown classes. 3) Integration with source-free domain adaptation methods for effective model adaptation to the target domain.	RRDA enhances SF-OSDA by explicitly learning representations for unknown classes through synthetic feature generation and by incorporating a target classifier to distinguish between known and unknown classes, thus overcoming the limitations of existing threshold-based methods.	Adaptation of AI models for real-world applications where not all possible classes are known beforehand, such as medical image diagnostics that must account for new, emerging diseases not represented in initial training data.	\N	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2411.12558", "title": "Recall and Refine Domain Adaptation (RRDA)"}]	{EPFL,"ETH Zürich"}
