40034015-e048-4eb7-95a3-a71c44258994	Lab-MAE	Enhance the accuracy and fairness of laboratory value imputation in electronic health records (EHRs) using a transformer-based masked autoencoder framework that captures temporal and contextual dependencies.	Traditional methods for imputing missing lab values in EHRs often fail to capture complex temporal and contextual dependencies, leading to biases and inaccuracies in clinical predictions. Existing approaches struggle with underrepresented populations, resulting in potential disparities in healthcare outcomes.	Development of a transformer model (Lab-MAE) for imputing missing laboratory values in clinical EHR data. It aims to provide equitable performance across different demographic groups and improve the overall quality of clinical data for decision-making.	["Healthcare providers","Hospitals","Clinical researchers","Health data analysts"]	Lab-MAE processes electronic health record data by using masked autoencoder architecture. It learns from existing lab value patterns to predict missing values based on temporal and contextual information embedded in the data. The model applies masking on a portion of input data during training, allowing it to learn to reconstruct these masked values effectively.	The Lab-MAE architecture includes an encoder-decoder setup with transformer blocks that leverage multi-head self-attention mechanisms. It processes both laboratory values and their corresponding timestamps, utilizing learned positional encodings to handle sequential data. Missing value attention masks prevent influence from missing data during processing.	Lab-MAE harnesses self-supervised learning through a transformer architecture to accurately impute missing lab values. It explicitly models temporal dependencies and ensures equitable performance across diverse demographic backgrounds, addressing biases inherent in traditional imputation methods. Additionally, its design minimizes carbon footprint by consolidating multiple tasks into a single model framework, enhancing efficiency.	Clinical decision support systems that require accurate lab value imputations for diagnosis, treatment planning, and patient monitoring. The model can be integrated into hospital information systems for real-time predictions and improvements in patient care.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/93/Seal_of_the_University_of_Michigan.svg/360px-Seal_of_the_University_of_Michigan.svg.png	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2501.02648", "title": "Lab-MAE"}]	{"Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT)","University of Michigan","Harvard Medical School","Northeastern University"}
c46ef3d8-8eb6-4641-9d0e-a94c5429e921	RSD-Enhancer	Enhance the efficiency of reasoning in large language models by implementing a Reward-Guided Speculative Decoding framework that optimizes inference processes and reduces computational costs while maintaining high accuracy.	Existing inference methods for large language models are computationally expensive and can lead to substantial processing delays, particularly in complex reasoning tasks. This issue hinders the deployment of language models in real-time applications. Additionally, purely speculative decoding methods may waste resources by frequently rejecting outputs, even when they are technically valid, leading to inefficiencies.	The framework aims to automate and enhance inference processes for large language models across various reasoning tasks, providing a more efficient decoding method that adapts to the computational needs of the task at hand, without sacrificing output fidelity.	["AI researchers","Data scientists","Software developers","Companies developing AI applications","Educational institutions focusing on AI research"]	The RSD framework combines a lightweight draft model to generate potential outputs and a more powerful target model to validate and enhance these outputs. It uses a reward-guided approach, where draft outputs are scored based on their predicted effectiveness. Outputs that meet a certain reward threshold are accepted; those that do not trigger the target model to refine them. This process minimizes unnecessary computations by selectively engaging the target model only when needed.	The system consists of two main components: a Draft Model and a Target Model. The Draft Model generates candidate outputs which are scored using a reward function. Depending on the score, these candidates are either accepted directly or sent to the Target Model for further evaluation. A process reward model is integrated to provide feedback at each decoding step, and the output distribution is dynamically adjusted based on predefined thresholds.	RSD introduces a controlled bias in speculative decoding, allowing for a more flexible response to candidate outputs based on their computed rewards. This method enhances overall efficiency by reducing reliance on the full power of the larger model and ensuring computational resources are only utilized when absolutely necessary. The use of a reward model at each step provides a structured approach to evaluating the effectiveness of outputs and informing subsequent decisions.	RSD can be applied in various scenarios requiring efficient reasoning, such as educational aids that assist in learning complex mathematics, extensions for real-time chatbots that need to respond promptly and accurately, and tools for researchers analyzing complex datasets where traditional models fall short.	https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Amsterdamuniversitylogo.svg	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2501.19324", "title": "RSD-Enhancer"}]	{"Salesforce AI Research","University of Amsterdam","California Institute of Technology"}
34f8a990-44ef-4451-8b1e-e7dd70205a5d	CREStE Navigator	To provide advanced, scalable, and robust mapless navigation solutions for autonomous vehicles and robots by leveraging internet-scale visual priors and counterfactual learning techniques.	Current mapless navigation systems often struggle with generalization to unseen urban environments, requiring frequent human interventions and suffering from insufficient understanding of complex terrain and dynamic elements. There is a need for a system that can navigate efficiently without pre-existing maps and adapts to novel situations.	Networked and modular mapless navigation system for urban, off-road, and residential environments, capable of long-distance travel with minimal human intervention. Supports various platforms such as ground vehicles and service robots.	["Autonomous vehicle manufacturers","Robotics companies","Urban delivery services","Research institutions","Smart city developers"]	The system utilizes a perceptual encoder to process RGB and depth data from onboard sensors, converting this information into structured bird’s-eye view (BEV) representations. It employs a counterfactual inverse reinforcement learning approach to learn navigation costs based on expert demonstrations, enabling it to predict effective paths and minimize the need for human intervention during navigation.	The architecture consists of a perceptual encoder for data processing, a BEV map generator for spatial reasoning, and a reward function that estimates costs associated with various paths. It employs a modular design for easy integration of new sensors and improved learning algorithms, with an active learning loop for updating policies based on counterfactuals.	The inclusion of counterfactual guidance in learning navigation costs enables the system to improve continuously with minimal intervention. The use of advanced visual foundation models (VFM) ensures robust and generalizable feature learning, surpassing traditional methods that rely solely on geometric or task-specific data.	Autonomous delivery vehicles using CREStE to navigate city streets without predefined maps, thereby saving time and reducing operational costs. Additionally, it can be applied in remote search and rescue operations or urban maintenance tasks.	\N	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2503.03921", "title": "CREStE Navigator"}]	{"The University of Texas at Austin","Autonomous Mobile Robotics Laboratory","Machine Decision-making through Interaction Laboratory"}
90ce927c-8421-4a1c-9b2d-11b6dd7f09ca	Amber	Enhance the quality of open-domain Question Answering (QA) by utilizing adaptive memory-based optimization for more accurate responses while minimizing irrelevant information.	Current Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) methods struggle with complex, open-domain QA tasks due to independent retrieval operations that lead to information noise and insufficient integration of knowledge. Existing systems also face inefficiencies due to uninformed retrieval strategies.	Utilization of Amber for improving QA tasks across various applications. The project encompasses the development of a comprehensive system for retrieving, filtering, and integrating knowledge from external datasets into a language model's memory.	["Research institutions","Educational platforms","Customer support systems","Information retrieval services"]	Amber leverages three core components: the Agent-based Memory Updater (AMU), which collaboratively integrates knowledge from past retrievals; the Adaptive Information Collector (AIC), which optimizes retrieval queries based on current memory; and the Multi-granular Content Filter (MCF), which filters out irrelevant data to retain essential information. This system iteratively updates memory and retrieval strategies to refine responses.	The system architecture includes an input interface for user queries, a retrieval module that uses a document corpus to fetch relevant texts, and three processing layers (AMU, AIC, MCF) that iteratively update language model memory. Outputs are managed through a response generation mechanism that synthesizes the final answer.	Amber integrates multi-agent collaboration for memory updates, enhancing knowledge integration across retrieval iterations. The adaptive filtering reduces the noise from irrelevant text, while the dynamic querying streamlines the information retrieval process, ensuring only the most relevant data is used for generating answers.	Customer service chatbots can utilize Amber to provide accurate and relevant answers based on previous interactions and up-to-date knowledge, enhancing user experience.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/3/3c/Logo_of_University_of_Science_and_Technology_of_China.svg/300px-Logo_of_University_of_Science_and_Technology_of_China.svg.png	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2504.05312", "title": "Amber"}]	{"University of Science and Technology of China","Hefei Institutes of Physical Science, Chinese Academy of Sciences"}
cdca15e5-3529-41ea-bed6-e9473ec6a7ea	Materialist	Enable precise and physically based image editing from a single image through inverse rendering methods, enhancing creativity and accuracy in the production of visual content.	Current image editing techniques lack the ability to accurately manipulate material properties like transparency and metallic effects in a physically consistent manner. Existing methods often neglect the physics of light interaction, leading to unrealistic results and a reliance on complex multi-view data.	Single-image inverse rendering for material editing, object insertion, and relighting. The service aims to offer a user-friendly interface for artists and designers to manipulate images with high physical fidelity.	["Graphic designers","Visual effects artists","Digital content creators","Architects","Marketing teams"]	The system starts by predicting material properties using a neural network. It then optimizes an environment map to refine lighting conditions and utilizes differentiable rendering to enable image adjustments while maintaining physical correctness. Users can edit properties such as albedo, roughness, metallic, and transparency directly from an image, generating new outputs in real-time.	1. Input Module: Receives a single image. 2. Material Prediction Network (MatNet): Predicts material properties (albedo, roughness, metallic). 3. Environment Map Optimization: Uses a multi-layer perceptron (MLP) to estimate lighting conditions. 4. Differentiable Renderer: Simulates realistic rendering based on predicted properties and optimized lighting. 5. Output Module: Displays final edited images with modifications.	The integration of neural predictions with physically based rendering allows for realistic edits in transparency and other complex material properties without requiring multi-view inputs. The system also significantly speeds up processing times compared to existing methods, achieving results in real-time.	The product can be utilized in commercial photography for product retouching, in film production for visual effects, in architectural rendering to visualize materials, and in e-commerce for product customization interfaces.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/Logo_of_the_Technical_University_of_Munich.svg/360px-Logo_of_the_Technical_University_of_Munich.svg.png	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2501.03717", "title": "Materialist"}]	{"Lezhong Wang, Technical University of Denmark","Duc Minh Tran, Technical University of Denmark","Ruiqi Cui, Technical University of Denmark","Thomson TG, Technical University of Denmark","Anders Bjorholm Dahl, Technical University of Denmark","Siavash Arjomand Bigdeli, Technical University of Denmark","Jeppe Revall Frisvad, Technical University of Denmark","Manmohan Chandraker, University of California San Diego"}
45422719-ec3e-4aa5-ac2a-76773b10c8e1	PP-DocBee	Enhance the understanding of multimodal document images through a robust AI model that accurately parses and interprets complex content including text, tables, and charts.	Existing models struggle with parsing and understanding document images, particularly in Chinese contexts, leading to inaccuracies and inefficiencies in document processing. Traditional OCR methods often fall short when faced with complex layouts and contextual reasoning.	End-to-end document image understanding, focusing on text-rich documents, tables, and charts. The system will integrate with various document management solutions for improved workflow automation.	["Corporations","Academic institutions","Legal firms","Research organizations"]	PP-DocBee employs a multimodal large language model (MLLM) architecture combining visual encoders (ViT) and text generation (LLM). It processes document images, extracting and understanding content using a synthesize-enhance method that includes dynamic sampling, data preprocessing, and OCR post-processing strategies. The system generates question-answer pairs to train and improve comprehension capabilities.	The model architecture consists of three main components: Image Processing Module: Uses ViT to extract visual features from document images. Large Language Model: Takes extracted features and contextualizes them for generating accurate interpretations and responses. Data Synthesis & QA Generation: Employs advanced synthesis methods to create diverse training datasets and validate model performance through generated question-answer pairs.	Introduction of a tailored data synthesis strategy for document images in Chinese, enhancing the dataset quality and model adaptability. The dynamic sampling training technique provides an optimization layer, allowing the model to prioritize higher-quality data for training without altering the model's architecture.	Corporations can automate the extraction of information from contracts and financial documents. Academic institutions can efficiently analyze and categorize research publications. Legal firms can expedite document review processes through enhanced parsing capabilities.	\N	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2503.04065", "title": "PP-DocBee"}]	{"PaddlePaddle Team","Baidu Inc."}
435b62ec-142f-4b10-98b5-a9aab2369239	TracLLM	Develop a generic framework for tracing the contributions of text segments in long context LLMs to improve the trust, accuracy, and reliability of generated outputs.	Existing methods for identifying text contributions in LLM-generated outputs suffer from high computational costs and inefficiencies, especially when dealing with long contexts. Traditional feature attribution methods are either sub-optimal or too demanding for practical use.	Application in any LLM integration where the accuracy of outputs based on extensive contextual information is critical, including debugging, forensic analysis, and validating generated content.	["AI developers","Data scientists","Cybersecurity professionals","LLM researchers"]	TracLLM employs an informed search algorithm combined with perturbation-based feature attribution techniques, such as the Shapley value, to efficiently identify the top K texts contributing to the output of an LLM from a long context. It iteratively narrows down candidate texts to determine key contributors.	TracLLM consists of multiple modules including Input Handling for the LLM, Context Segmentation to manage long texts, Contribution Scoring using perturbation methods, Group Pruning to efficiently reduce the search space, and Output Generation to present the identified texts and their importance.	TracLLM introduces a hybrid approach integrating contribution score denoising and a scoring ensemble method to improve the accuracy and reliability of output attribution in long context LLMs, making it distinct from previous methods.	Post-attack forensic analysis to identify malicious text inputs leading to incorrect outputs, enhancing the accuracy of LLM outputs in applications like customer support or information retrieval.	\N	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.04202", "title": "TracLLM"}]	{"Pennsylvania State University"}
179ea15d-5a9f-40d1-b601-85f92caabc33	UP-VLA	Enhance robotic decision-making in multi-modal environments by unifying vision, language understanding, and predictive capabilities for embodied agents.	Existing Vision-Language-Action (VLA) models often struggle with capturing detailed visual and spatial information necessary for performing complex tasks in dynamic environments, leading to limitations in real-world robotic applications.	Integration of multi-modal understanding and future predictive capabilities to elevate robotic control in both simulated and real-world scenarios. This includes training on multi-modal datasets, action learning, and iterative fine-tuning for specific tasks.	["Robotics companies","Automated supply chain solutions","Research institutes in robotics","AI developers interested in embodied agents"]	The UP-VLA model processes images and language instructions simultaneously, utilizing a unified architecture that enables it to predict future visual states while also understanding current environments. This involves training with diverse datasets that balance high-level semantic understanding and low-level spatial dynamics.	The architecture leverages an autoregressive model with three main components: multi-modal understanding, future visual prediction, and action generation. The input layer accepts language and image tokens; these are processed through encoder layers for feature extraction; the output modules predict future states and necessary actions for robotics.	UP-VLA introduces a novel training approach that combines visual prediction and multi-modal understanding to improve both task performance and generalization capabilities. This addresses limitations in existing VLA models by incorporating predictive elements alongside traditional understanding techniques.	Application in robotic manipulation tasks such as sorting objects, assembling components based on visual cues and language instructions, and generalizing learned actions to unseen environments with different objects.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ec/Tsinghua_University_Logo.svg/360px-Tsinghua_University_Logo.svg.png	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2501.18867", "title": "UP-VLA"}]	{"Tsinghua University","Shanghai Qi Zhi Institute","Collaborative Robotics Team"}
2dcf98ef-01b9-451b-a39e-8831643539ad	JointDiT	Enhance the capabilities of RGB-depth joint modeling by utilizing diffusion transformers for more accurate image and depth generation.	Current methods for generating images and depth maps often lack accurate representation and high fidelity. Traditional approaches address image generation or depth estimation separately, leading to inconsistencies and inaccuracies. A unified approach that effectively models the joint distribution of RGB images and depth maps is lacking.	Joint generation of RGB images and depth maps, depth estimation from images, and depth-conditioned image generation, applicable in various fields such as computer vision, augmented reality, and robotics.	["Computer vision researchers","Augmented reality developers","Gaming industry professionals","Robotics engineers","Autonomous vehicle manufacturers"]	JointDiT models the joint distribution of RGB images and depth maps through a diffusion transformer architecture. It employs adaptive scheduling weights to manage noise levels in each modality and an unbalanced timestep sampling strategy to allow for flexible combinatorial tasks such as joint generation and depth estimation.	JointDiT utilizes a diffusion transformer framework, integrating multi-modal diffusion transformer (MM-DiT) and parallel diffusion transformer (P-DiT) blocks. Each block has joint connection modules for exchanging features between RGB and depth branches. The unique architecture reinforces the joint distribution modelling across varying noise levels.	The introduction of adaptive scheduling weights and unbalanced timestep sampling, allowing for effective training across multiple modalities with distinct noise levels. This enables unparalleled flexibility in performing various tasks without needing separate models for each task.	JointDiT can be used for creating realistic 3D virtual environments from 2D images for gaming and simulation, aiding in robotic perception by generating depth information, and enhancing the performance of AR applications by improving depth accuracy.	\N	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.00482", "title": "JointDiT"}]	{POSTECH,"Microsoft Research Asia",KAIST}
249d2d84-0393-40e4-aad6-31a73f5131b0	A3 Compression Framework	To provide an efficient low-rank approximation method for deploying large language models (LLMs) that reduces model size and computational requirements without compromising performance.	Large language models often have billions of parameters, resulting in high computational and memory costs, which inhibit widespread deployment. Existing low-rank approximation methods do not fully leverage the architectural characteristics of transformer models and can introduce additional runtime overhead.	Post-training low-rank approximation framework specifically designed for transformers. Focus on compressing transformer components (QK, OV, MLP) while maintaining or improving overall model performance during inference.	["AI Developers","Machine Learning Engineers","Companies deploying large language models","Researchers in AI and Machine Learning"]	The A3 framework splits transformer layers into three components: QK, OV, and MLP. It employs analytical solutions to minimize functional errors within these components. This approach reduces hidden dimensions without introducing additional GEMM operations, thereby saving computation and memory resources.	A3 decomposes transformer layers into three key components. Each component is optimized separately to minimize functional errors, using low-rank approximations tailored to attention scores, outputs, and intermediate results. It is designed to prevent excessive runtime overhead and enhance model throughput during inference.	A3 provides a novel method of compressing transformer components that avoids the inefficiencies present in traditional low-rank approximation techniques. It offers computational advantages by maintaining the same number of GEMM operations while reducing the dimensionality of the transformer components.	A3 can be utilized for optimizing large language model deployments in cloud environments, enabling faster inference times and reduced resource costs, while maintaining high levels of performance across various tasks, such as language understanding and completion.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c5/Shield_of_Imperial_College_London.svg/330px-Shield_of_Imperial_College_London.svg.png	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.12942", "title": "A3 Compression Framework"}]	{"Imperial College London","Various industry collaborators","AI research institutions"}
004aeb34-fd48-4694-b398-bcb8861abd2d	GAN-RM	Simplify reward modeling in visual generative models to ensure better alignment with human preferences while reducing manual annotation costs.	Current reward modeling techniques require extensive human-annotated preference data, which is costly and time-consuming. The existing methods are often incomplete and engineering-intensive, leading to suboptimal generative model performance that does not align well with human preferences.	A robust reward modeling framework that utilizes a small set of unpaired target samples (Preference Proxy Data) to train generative models, allowing for improved quality and alignment with human expectations in image and video generation tasks.	["AI developers","Data scientists","Digital content creators","Research institutions","Technology companies"]	GAN-RM operates by comparing a limited set of representative human-preferred samples (Preference Proxy Data) to outputs from generative models. By leveraging adversarial learning, GAN-RM trains a reward model that can differentiate between high-quality outputs and ordinary samples without needing extensive manual labels. It performs multi-round post-training to refine generative model outputs iteratively based on evaluated preferences.	The architecture of GAN-RM includes a vision encoder (CLIP-Vision) to process input samples, a Reward Projection Layer (RPL) for binary classification between preference proxy data and generated outputs, and a bootstrapping mechanism that leverages additional data for improved accuracy. The RPL outputs a confidence score to assess sample quality, facilitating both sample selection and generator fine-tuning.	Unlike traditional methods, GAN-RM eliminates the need for extensive human preference annotation by using Preference Proxy Data. It allows for efficient training and alignment of generative models through a bootstrapping mechanism that iteratively refines the model's output quality without heavy engineering or large datasets. This approach is scalable across different tasks, from image to video generation.	Applying GAN-RM for improving output quality and safety in image generation, such as filtering unsafe content or optimizing visual coherence in generated assets. It also enables enhanced sample selection during the inference phase to boost overall output performance without requiring fine-tuning of the generative engine.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/44/Fudan_University_Logo.svg/500px-Fudan_University_Logo.svg.png	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.13846", "title": "GAN-RM"}]	{"Hong Kong University of Science and Technology","Fudan University","Johns Hopkins University"}
bb2d14a9-29be-48b8-abf7-c4ebb2f679ef	PCDVQ Implementation for Edge ML	To enable efficient deployment of large language models on edge devices by enhancing vector quantization accuracy via Polar Coordinate Decoupling and Distribution Aligned Codebook Construction.	Existing methods for quantizing large language models do not adequately address the differing sensitivities of vector directions and magnitudes, resulting in significant accuracy loss during low-bit quantization. This limits the ability to deploy these models on edge devices with restricted computational resources.	Implementation of Polar Coordinate Decoupled Vector Quantization (PCDVQ) framework for large language models, targeting edge deployment in real-time applications. Includes integration into various edge computing environments and adaptation to multiple LLM architectures.	["Machine Learning Engineers","Edge Computing Developers","AI Research Centers","Tech Companies specializing in Natural Language Processing"]	The PCDVQ framework converts high-dimensional vectors into polar coordinates to decouple the quantization of magnitude and direction. It uses separate codebooks for these components, optimizing accuracy in low-bit settings. The quantization process involves clustering both components with tailored algorithms to enhance representation in constrained environments.	The system consists of a preprocessing module for polar conversion, independent codebook construction modules for direction and magnitude, a quantization module using cosine similarity for direction and an optimal method for magnitude, and an integration layer for edge deployment.	The key innovations are the decoupling of direction and magnitude quantization that leads to reduced quantization error, and the use of distribution-aligned codebooks which enable a more representative quantization of directions and magnitudes relevant to their statistical properties.	Deploying compressed, high-accuracy language models on edge devices for applications such as on-device virtual assistants, smart IoT devices, and real-time language translation services.	\N	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.05432", "title": "PCDVQ Implementation for Edge ML"}]	{"Harbin Institute of Technology (Shenzhen)","Houmo AI"}
f472cd58-69a4-4782-b0a9-6707bfe0cb49	V2X-REALM	Enable robust and safe cooperative autonomous driving by utilizing vision-language models to navigate complex, long-tail scenarios effectively.	Existing autonomous driving systems struggle to perform reliably in rare and adverse conditions like heavy snow and fog, often resulting in safety risks. Current single-agent and cooperative frameworks lack sufficient adaptability to varied scenarios, leading to reduced performance and increased collision risks under such conditions. There's a need for a system that can maintain high accuracy and safety across diverse driving conditions.	End-to-end cooperative autonomous driving that integrates vehicle-to-everything (V2X) communication, multimodal perception, and adaptive long-tail scenario modeling. Application to urban settings with a focus on rare adverse weather conditions.	["Automotive manufacturers","Technology companies in autonomous driving","Urban planners","City transport authorities","Research institutions"]	V2X-REALM uses a vision-language model to process both vehicle-side and infrastructure-side visual inputs along with contextual scene descriptions. It employs a prompt-driven long-tail scenario generation method to create training data reflecting adverse conditions, enhancing model resilience. The gated multi-scenario adaptive attention module recalibrates features based on the perceived scenario, while the multi-task scenario-aware contrastive learning ensures robust multimodal alignment and domain separation during training.	The architecture consists of an image encoder that processes paired vehicle and infrastructure images to generate visual token embeddings. A gated multi-scenario adaptive attention (GMSAA) module applies scenario-specific priors to enhance visual representations. These embeddings are combined with text embeddings from a scene description encoder to create a unified representation. This is then fed into a transformer decoder to predict future