3d711893-8331-4858-9d4b-7c2f35e23bf3	SSE Planner	Enhance the performance and reliability of long-horizon goal-oriented tasks for reinforcement learning by enforcing strict subgoal execution and dynamic path refinement.	Achieving long-horizon goals in reinforcement learning can be difficult due to sparse rewards, leading to inefficient learning and unreliable subgoal reachability. Existing hierarchical methods do not adequately ensure subgoal feasibility and often require multiple steps to reach a final goal, resulting in unstable training and high complexity.	Implementation of the Strict Subgoal Execution framework for long-horizon goal-conditioned tasks in reinforcement learning, focusing on efficient planning with dynamic adjustments. Application in diverse environments requiring robust agent navigation and multi-goal completion.	["AI researchers","Robotics developers","Automated decision systems","Game developers"]	The SSE framework utilizes a hierarchical structure that enforces a single-step subgoal completion model. It combines a high-level policy for subgoal selection with a low-level execution policy for navigation. The system employs a graph-based approach to create a map of the goal space, allowing agents to plan paths dynamically while adapting to failure rates in their execution environment. Failure-aware path refinement is included to optimize route selection away from potential pitfalls.	The architecture includes: 1. High-Level Decision Policy (πh) for selecting goals and subgoals from a designed graph. 2. Exploration Policy (πexp) that targets under-explored areas of the goal space. 3. Low-Level Execution Policy (πl) that performs actions based on selected subgoals. 4. A graph representation of the environment encompassing nodes as subgoals and edges representing possible transitions with associated costs.	The SSE offers innovative single-step subgoal execution to enhance the reliability of goal completion in straightforward surveyable actions. Additionally, it introduces failure-aware path refinement to adjust edge traversal costs based on historical success rates, which improves overall execution efficiency and adaptability in uncertain environments.	Utilizing SSE in robotic navigation tasks where robots must efficiently navigate to several strategic locations while avoiding obstacles and minimizing failure. Suitable for training AI in multi-goal environments requiring sequential decision-making.	\N	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.21039", "title": "SSE Planner"}]	{"UNIST Graduate School of Artificial Intelligence"}
edf6c462-fe5a-410c-b475-97bf5acd0aa4	Skyrmion-Bimeron Encoder System	To harness all-electric control of skyrmion and bimeron states in van der Waals heterostructures for advanced low-power spintronic applications.	Current spintronic devices often rely on external magnetic fields for control, which can lead to higher power consumption and complexity in integration. There is a need for systems that can be efficiently manipulated using only electrical signals, offering greater flexibility and energy efficiency.	Development of a system capable of reversible transitions between magnetic skyrmions and bimerons using electric control in van der Waals heterostructures. Applications in data storage and processing, utilizing the inherent stability and unique properties of these topological textures.	["Electronics manufacturers","Research institutions","University laboratories","Technology developers"]	The system employs a MoTeI/In2Se3 multiferroic heterostructure. By reversing the ferroelectric polarization in the In2Se3 layer, the magnetic anisotropy of the MoTeI layer is controlled, enabling the transition between skyrmion and bimeron states. The resulting topological spin textures can be manipulated for information encoding in a power-efficient manner.	The architecture consists of a MoTeI monolayer layer stack on an In2Se3 layer. The input layer receives electric signals, which modulate the ferroelectric polarization. The magnetic properties are calculated using first-principles methods, influencing the stability of skyrmion and bimeron arrangements. Micromagnetic simulations verify the transition process.	This project features the first demonstration of a dynamic skyrmion-bimeron transition controlled entirely through electric fields, eliminating the need for magnetic fields. The binary encoding scheme allows for multiple state configurations, enhancing data storage possibilities and energy efficiency in skyrionic devices.	The proposed system can be applied for high-speed data storage and retrieval in racetrack memory architectures, enabling faster access and lower energy consumption in memory devices. It can also function as a binary encoder using skyrmion and bimeron states as bits.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/0/09/CUHK_Coat_of_Arms.png	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.20984", "title": "Skyrmion-Bimeron Encoder System"}]	{"The Chinese University of Hong Kong, Shenzhen","Waseda University","Guizhou University","Shanxi Normal University","Hunan University"}
87e6bb30-66ef-4bb4-8f61-63d125b086c2	GraphTest Pro	Enhance hypothesis testing in random graph models using advanced likelihood ratio tests to provide robust statistical insights for complex networks.	Existing statistical methods for testing hypotheses in random graph models struggle with increasing dimensionality and often yield inaccurate or non-interpretative results. There is a need for more reliable statistical approaches that can accommodate large parameter spaces while providing meaningful insights.	Implement adaptive likelihood ratio tests for random graphs, accommodating models like the β-model and Bradley-Terry model. Enable applications in real-world network analyses with appropriate tools to manage increasing dimensions in hypothesis testing.	["Data scientists","Statisticians","Network analysts","Research institutions"]	GraphTest Pro uses the normalized log-likelihood ratio statistic to assess hypotheses in random graph structures, converging to known distributions as the number of nodes increases. It utilizes advanced statistical techniques to ensure robustness and accuracy in estimating parameters and testing hypotheses.	The system architecture consists of a high-level integration module for data input from various networks, a likelihood ratio testing engine that computes statistics based on input data, and an output reporting module that presents results visually and analytically. The integration of the statistical engine allows for real-time processing of large datasets.	Adapting classical likelihood ratio tests to high-dimensional settings while ensuring the Wilks phenomenon is realized. The introduction of novel asymptotic expansions and robust statistical techniques that aggregate network data seamlessly enhances the accuracy of hypothesis testing.	GraphTest Pro can be used in academia for research on social networks, in policy-making for analyzing social media interactions, and in various sectors where network data must be analyzed to identify significant relationships or patterns.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/3/3c/Logo_of_University_of_Science_and_Technology_of_China.svg/300px-Logo_of_University_of_Science_and_Technology_of_China.svg.png	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2311.05806", "title": "GraphTest Pro"}]	{"Central China Normal University","George Washington University","City University of Hong Kong","University of Science and Technology of China","University of Michigan"}
