fidelity to source images is required while implementing specific desired modifications, such as in advertising, digital media content creation, and photo editing applications.	\N	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.21045", "title": "DiffusionFaithful Editor"}]	{"Korea University"}
e42d9ce8-d321-41cb-8fd3-ac66e3d48d96	FeDa4Fair	Enhance the benchmarking of fairness-aware federated learning methods by generating and providing access to client-level federated datasets reflecting heterogeneous bias distributions.	Current federated learning methods often do not account for biases present in individual client datasets, leading to unfair outcomes across different demographic groups. Existing evaluations typically prioritize a single sensitive attribute, neglecting the diverse fairness needs of multiple clients and thus potentially exacerbating unfairness.	Creation of multi-client federated datasets capable of demonstrating varying biases across attributes and attribute values; evaluation of fairness across global and client-specific dimensions; tools for practical implementation in federated learning environments.	["Machine learning researchers","Data scientists","Academics in AI ethics and fairness","Developers of federated learning systems"]	FeDa4Fair generates benchmark federated datasets by leveraging parameters that define client bias distributions based on sensitive attributes. It produces tabular datasets tailored for evaluating fairness across multiple clients and heterogeneous bias conditions, while also providing metrics for demographic disparity and equalized odds for performance assessment.	The FeDa4Fair library is integrated into the Flower framework, featuring three main components: Dataset Generation Module (creates bias-heterogeneous datasets), Fairness Evaluation Module (calculates metrics at client-level), and Documentation & Data Sheet Generation Module (produces datasheets for reproducibility).	FeDa4Fair offers a unique approach to benchmarking federated learning by allowing systematic modifications of data biases to suit diverse scenarios, enabling researchers to evaluate fairness at both global and client-specific levels, as opposed to traditional single-attribute evaluation strategies.	Evaluation of federated learning models under varying demographic conditions; benchmarking fairness-aware solutions in controlled environments; assisting developers in creating fairness-enhanced machine learning systems.	\N	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.21095", "title": "FeDa4Fair"}]	{"Institute of Computer Science, Johannes Gutenberg University Mainz","KDD Lab, University of Pisa"}
