9a7a2b69-d8b8-45ea-82d6-51488cc0a549	Mind2Web 2	To provide a comprehensive benchmark for evaluating agentic search systems, focusing on long-horizon and realistic tasks by utilizing an innovative Agent-as-a-Judge evaluation framework.	Existing evaluation methodologies for agentic search systems primarily focus on short tasks with static answers, failing to address the complexity and variability of longer, real-time search tasks. There is a need for an evaluation framework that can handle diverse, time-varying information retrieval tasks.	Creation of a benchmark consisting of 130 diverse and realistic long-horizon tasks that require extensive information gathering from multiple web sources. Development of an Agent-as-a-Judge framework for evaluating the correctness and attribution of answers generated by agentic search systems.	["AI researchers","Developers of agentic search systems","Academic institutions","Technology companies","Research organizations"]	The project consists of a benchmark containing complex web search tasks which are evaluated using the Agent-as-a-Judge framework. Tasks require an AI agent to autonomously retrieve, interpret, and answer complex queries by navigating multiple web sources. Each task comes with a detailed rubric that consists of multiple criteria checked at various levels to assess answer correctness and source attribution.	The architecture includes a task collection module, a judge agent framework, a rubric management system, an extractor for information retrieval from answers, and a verifier for checking claims against designated webpages. The system flow starts with task execution by the agent, followed by information extraction and then evaluation using the Agent-as-a-Judge framework.	The introduction of an Agent-as-a-Judge framework that utilizes a tree-structured rubric for systematically evaluating complex answers generated by agentic search systems, allowing for automated evaluation of multi-step reasoning tasks. The benchmark