0de96a4f-afaa-472f-b4c5-08674625305e	PDE Bridge	Facilitate the understanding and modeling of complex biological systems by leveraging PDE discovery methods to connect micro-scale dynamics with macro-scale behavior.	Biological systems exhibit non-linear behaviors across multiple spatial and temporal scales, complicating the modeling and understanding of their dynamics. Traditional modeling methods often fail to capture the emergent properties present when moving from molecular interactions to whole-cell simulations. There is a significant need for tools that can effectively leverage micro-scale data to inform macro-scale models.	Integration of PDE discovery methodologies with particle-based simulations to model calcium dynamics in astrocytes, enabling the translation of micro-scale behaviors into macro-scale predictions. The approach combines computational simulations with data-driven discovery of governing equations to facilitate accurate biological modeling.	["Research institutions","Biotechnology companies","Pharmaceutical companies","Academics in computational biology","Healthcare technology firms"]	1. Data Generation: Utilize particle-based simulations to generate synthetic data representing calcium ion diffusion at a micro-scale. 2. Local Simulation: Run simulations across various spatial patches to obtain local particle density fields. 3. Mean Field Computation: Compute mean fields from local simulations to create datasets for PDE discovery. 4. PDE Discovery: Apply state-of-the-art PDE discovery methods to extract governing equations from the spatio-temporal data. 5. Macro Simulation: Use the discovered PDEs to simulate the whole-cell dynamics based on the initial conditions derived from micro-scale data.	1. Data Input Layer: Receives parameters for particle-based simulations (initial conditions, diffusion rates). 2. Simulation Engine: Executes particle simulations to generate datasets for calcium diffusion. 3. Data Processing Unit: Analyzes simulation outputs