a886e800-7a56-48c6-9c70-482e54993858	ClusterRCA	Enhance the efficiency and accuracy of network failure diagnosis in high-performance computing (HPC) systems by leveraging multimodal data integration and advanced classification methods.	Traditional methods of diagnosing network failures in HPC systems are often ineffective due to the heterogeneity of data from various components, leading to challenges in accurately localizing the root cause and classifying failure types. Existing solutions struggle to deal with the complex topologies and correlations in HPC networks, resulting in potential downtime and inefficiencies.	Comprehensive diagnostic tool for network failures in HPC systems through analysis of logs and metrics from compute nodes and network switches, focused on enhancing troubleshooting processes and minimizing system downtime.	["HPC system administrators","Data center operators","IT departments in research institutions","Cloud service providers"]	ClusterRCA integrates logs and metrics from both compute nodes and network switches into feature vectors. It employs a state classifier to rank the probabilistic state of network components (culprit, victim, normal) and utilizes a customized random walk algorithm to pinpoint the exact cause of failures. This dual approach enhances diagnosis accuracy and reliability.	The architecture consists of two main phases: offline training using historical logs and metrics to create feature vectors and online diagnosis that utilizes real-time data for classification and random walk localization. It includes modules for feature extraction, state classification, and failure diagnosis that interact to provide actionable insights.	ClusterRCA introduces a novel integration of classifier-based and graph-based methods for enhanced accuracy in diagnosing network failures. The use of NIC pairs in feature engineering allows for tailored analysis of the interconnected nature of HPC systems, improving the functioning of both classification and localization processes.	Effective localization of network-related failures in HPC environments, aiding operators in quickly identifying and remediating issues related to compute nodes and network switches. Suitable for environments requiring high availability and performance, such as scientific research computing, simulations, and big data processing.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/b/b9/NUS_coat_of_arms.svg/260px-NUS_coat_of_arms.svg.png	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.20673", "title": "ClusterRCA"}]	{"Nankai University","National University of Defense Technology",Huawei}
