edd9d131-831a-49ec-b4fb-65aec04876d1	IMC-PINN-FE	To provide rapid, patient-specific left ventricular finite element modeling that utilizes physics-informed neural networks for biomechanical analysis, enhancing clinical applicability and efficiency.	Existing finite element modeling approaches for cardiac biomechanics are time-consuming, demanding real-time iteration and complex datasets. Conventional methods often cannot ensure fidelity to observed cardiac motion, leading to ineffective patient-specific models. There is a need for an efficient and accurate framework that can reproduce observed cardiac dynamics while estimating biomechanical parameters swiftly.	Development of a framework for modeling left ventricular mechanics across the cardiac cycle with a focus on computational efficiency and accuracy. Emphasis on patient-specific cases derived from 4D MRI or echocardiographic imaging.	["Cardiologists","Medical Imaging Professionals","Biomedical Engineers","Healthcare Institutions"]	The framework first derives cardiac motion from 4D imaging through deep learning models. It then utilizes physics-informed neural networks to estimate muscle stiffness and contractile dynamics based on pressure measurements, enabling fast finite element simulations that accurately reflect cardiac motion across the cycle.	The system comprises three main components: 1) Deep Learning Motion Tracking using 4D cardiac images to obtain motion fields and geometrical shapes; 2) A Myocardial Stiffness and Maximal Tension Estimator using physics-based governing equations derived from the acquired motion; 3) A Volume-Constrained PINN-FE Solver that integrates estimated parameters to simulate left ventricular dynamics over the cardiac cycle while satisfying motion constraints.	IMC-PINN-FE integrates image-derived motion consistency with biomechanical simulations, which boosts computational efficiency by reducing computation times from several hours to minutes. It promotes accurate patient-specific 