7d9e483f-ba32-42be-afab-cf6a41bef06e	Size-Based Adaptive Federated Learning (SAFL)	To establish a transformative framework for federated learning that systematically organizes training processes based on dataset size characteristics and modality types, enhancing effectiveness and efficiency in multi-modal data systems while preserving privacy.	Existing federated learning techniques primarily focus on model heterogeneity and aggregation without adequately addressing how dataset size affects learning dynamics. This oversight has led to performance issues and inefficiencies, particularly with heterogeneous multi-modal data, resulting in suboptimal model training and communicative overhead.	Development of a size-based adaptive framework for federated learning that includes progressive training strategies, cross-modal performance analyses, and real-time system monitoring for various types of datasets (vision, text, time series, audio, sensor, medical vision, multimodal).	["Data Scientists","Machine Learning Engineers","Researchers in AI","Organizations requiring data privacy","Healthcare institutions","Financial services providers"]	The framework organizes federated learning by prioritizing smaller datasets for training, progressively increasing in size. It employs adaptive parameter tuning based on dataset characteristics and modality complexity. A comprehensive monitoring system tracks performance metrics and optimizes communication protocols.	The SAFL framework consists of four layers: 1) Multi-Modal Dataset Discovery - collects and profiles datasets. 2) Progressive Training Strategy - organizes training by dataset size. 3) Adaptive Aggregation - selects aggregation methods based on complexity. 4) Real-Time Monitoring Infrastructure - provides feedback on system performance and network efficiency.	SAFL's primary innovations include its systematic size-based training methodology, comprehensive performance hierarchy across diverse modalities, integrated real-time monitoring capabilities, and adaptability in parameter selection based on dataset characteristics. This allows for optimized performance and improved convergence in federated learning scenarios.	The SAFL framework can be applied in healthcare systems for analyzing patient data across multiple clinics while ensuring confidentiality, in financial technology for risk assessment using client data, and in smart cities for analyzing sensor data from multiple sources without aggregating raw data.	\N	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.20685", "title": "Size-Based Adaptive Federated Learning (SAFL)"}]	{"Military College of Signals, NUST","University of Sciences and Technology, Islamabad"}
9516f270-2974-4f43-8eda-0bcb67e68abb	Diffusion Tree Sampling (DTS)	Enable scalable inference-time alignment of pretrained diffusion models to produce high-quality generative outputs under user-defined objectives and diverse reward functions without the need for retraining.	Traditional methods for adapting pretrained diffusion models at inference time face challenges such as high computational costs, bias in value estimation, and an inability to reuse information from past computations, leading to inefficient sample quality. These issues hinder the effective guidance of the diffusion process based on unseen rewards.	Inference-time alignment and generation of samples from diffusion models for varying objectives, including class-conditional generation, text-to-image synthesis, and language completion, while effectively utilizing computational resources.	["AI researchers","Data scientists","Software engineers","Creative professionals","Businesses in media and design"]	DTS operates by framing the denoising process of diffusion models as a tree search problem. Each node in the tree represents a state in the noise transition process. The algorithm selects paths based on estimated rewards, performing rollouts to refine soft value estimates. It uses a Monte Carlo Tree Search (MCTS) approach to propagate rewards back through the chain, optimizing sample generation with minimal additional compute.	The architecture consists of a tree structure where nodes represent noisy states, and edges represent denoising transitions. Each node maintains soft value estimates and visit counts, allowing for continuous updates as the tree builds. The four main phases include selection, expansion, rollout, and backup, facilitating efficient sample generation and refinement.	The use of a tree-based sampling mechanism which allows the algorithm to reuse past computations and improve sample quality dynamically. The approach significantly reduces computational requirements, matching state-of-the-art results with less than half the compute resources, and provides a systematic way to optimize sample quality at inference time.	Applications in various generative tasks such as generating class-conditional image samples from diffusion models, creating high-quality text-to-image outputs that align with complex prompts, and enhancing text generation performance with diverse outputs based on classification rewards.	\N	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.20701", "title": "Diffusion Tree Sampling (DTS)"}]	{"McGill University","Mila - Quebec Artificial Intelligence Institute"}
