f820cf1e-9db6-46d1-bf1b-c5c7ec27394f	LLTBoost	Enhance model interpretability and efficiency in additive rule ensembles by introducing learnable sparse linear transformations, allowing for oblique decision boundaries while maintaining predictive performance.	Traditional rule ensembles rely on a limited set of features, leading to high interpretability but poor predictive accuracy when faced with complex datasets. Existing methods often result in models that lack sufficient complexity to capture the necessary patterns in the data without compromising interpretability.	Reduction of model complexity in predictive modeling through interpretable rule-based frameworks applicable across various domains such as finance, healthcare, and marketing.	["Data scientists","Machine learning engineers","Business analysts","Regulatory compliance teams"]	The LLTBoost method leverages structured additive ensembles where predictions are generated from a combination of symbolic rules with oblique decision boundaries. Each rule condition is formed using sparse linear transformations of input features, enabling the model to flexibly partition the input space. A sequential greedy optimization approach is used to build the model iteratively, optimizing for minimal complexity while maintaining low prediction risk.	The system consists of three primary layers: Propositions Layer (propositions defined by linear transformations of input variables), Conjunctions Layer (logical 'AND' operations on propositions), and Rule Weight Layer (combination of weighted rules for final output). Each layer integrates to form a deep architectural representation of rule ensembles.	The introduction of learnable sparse linear transformations expands the capability of traditional axis-parallel decision boundaries to oblique ones, enhancing both complexity and interpretability of the predictions. This bridges the gap between interpretability and predictive power.	This model can be utilized in industries needing interpretable, low-complexity predictions such as credit scoring, where decisions must be transparent and regulatory compliant.	\N	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.20927", "title": "LLTBoost"}]	{"Monash University","University of Haifa"}
63da4812-42f6-4feb-ac9a-d07694eba5ea	GRAPH-AID	To generate reliable adverse event profiles in healthcare by automating ontology building and integrating diverse data sources for better drug safety monitoring.	The rapid growth of healthcare data, particularly concerning adverse drug events, poses challenges in effectively organizing, retrieving, and utilizing this information for public health decisions. Traditional methods for ontology creation are complex and require specialized knowledge, creating barriers for broader accessibility and timely responses to public health concerns.	Integration of FDA Adverse Event Reporting System (FAERS) and Vaccine Adverse Event Reporting System (VAERS) data into a Neo4j database and generating an OWL ontology for semantic representation of drug adverse events.	["Public health researchers","Regulatory agencies","Pharmaceutical companies","Healthcare providers","Data scientists"]	Raw adverse event data from the FAERS is exported in XML format, converted to JSON, and ingested into a Neo4j graph database. A Python script utilizing the rdflib library generates the required classes and axioms automatically for ontology creation, linking entities based on their relationships in the data. The generated ontology can then be utilized for hypothesis generation and enhanced retrieval of adverse event profiles.	Data Collection: Data is collected from FAERS and VAERS databases. Data Transformation: XML is converted to JSON to preserve hierarchical structures. Neo4j Database Creation: JSON data is ingested into a Neo4j graph database using Cypher queries. Ontology Construction: Classes and relationships from the Neo4j database are extracted and used to create an OWL ontology with the rdflib library, which is then serialized for use.	Automation of ontology generation that decreases reliance on specialized knowledge in logics. Enables real-time integration of extensive public health datasets to form a knowledge graph. Increased accessibility and usability of complex healthcare data for researchers and agencies without deep technical expertise.	Healthcare professionals can utilize the generated ontology to identify potential adverse drug interactions or trends in adverse event reporting, aiding in drug safety evaluations and public health responses.	\N	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.20851", "title": "GRAPH-AID"}]	{"Kansas State University","U.S. Food and Drug Administration"}
526867d7-d2a9-41fb-8616-8503f377c8a0	VideoTex	Transform 3D texture synthesis by achieving seamless, temporally coherent textures through geometry-aware diffusion and component-based UV mapping.	Traditional techniques for 3D texture synthesis often lead to visible seams and spatial inconsistencies, especially in dynamic environments. The reliance on fixed viewpoints and inadequate handling of occluded regions exacerbate these issues, resulting in textures that lack fidelity and coherence.	Development of a video-generation approach for seamless 3D texture synthesis that maintains high spatial and temporal consistency across various viewpoints, suitable for dynamic and immersive environments.	["Game developers","Virtual reality designers","3D modelers","Filmmakers","Animation studios"]	The VideoTex framework formulates texture generation as a video generation problem, utilizing video generation models to produce coherent textures across multiple viewpoints. It leverages geometry-aware conditioning through normal, depth, and edge maps, followed by component-wise UV diffusion to refine occluded regions.	VideoTex operates in a two-stage process: 1) Texture generation using video-based models conditioned on 3D geometric information. 2) UV-based texture refinement to inpaint occluded areas, ensuring high-quality output.	VideoTex uniquely combines video generation techniques with geometry-awareness for texture synthesis, enabling smooth transitions and coherence across dynamic angles. It employs component-wise UV diffusion to maintain semantic integrity, significantly outperforming traditional methods in texture fidelity and consistency.	Application in video games and simulations for creating realistic 3D environments with dynamically generated textures that adapt to changing perspectives without loss of quality.	\N	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.20946", "title": "VideoTex"}]	{"Chung-Ang University",NCSOFT,"University of Seoul"}
2b7d7cd0-78da-484f-a23b-9b2a46566d21	OmniEval Benchmark	Provide a comprehensive evaluation platform for omni-modal models that integrate visual, auditory, and textual inputs to enhance performance in real-world AI applications.	Existing benchmarks inadequately evaluate omni-modal models as they typically concentrate on one or two modalities, overlooking the synergistic understanding derived from concurrent processing of dynamic visual, auditory, and textual information.	Assess models' capabilities across diverse tasks involving full-modal collaboration, grounding, and understanding in both English and Chinese across 810 video clips and 2617 question-answer pairs.	["AI Researchers","AI Developers","Multimodal AI Companies","Educational Institutions","Content Creation Studios"]	OmniEval combines audio, video, and text inputs into a concise testing framework which includes open-ended and multiple-choice questions. Models are evaluated on their ability to leverage all modalities to provide accurate responses while connecting temporal elements for grounding tasks.	OmniEval consists of a data collection module for diverse video sourcing, an Automated Speech Recognition (ASR) system for audio-transcript generation, and a QA generation pipeline using large models for producing and classifying question-answer pairs. Performance evaluation is conducted based on distinct scoring methods for ground truths of various task types.	Offers bilingual support for diverse evaluations (English and Chinese), emphasizes open-ended questions to gauge generative capabilities, integrates grounding tasks for precise temporal localization of answers, and provides a holistic performance analysis across cognitive faculties.	Researchers can use OmniEval to benchmark and improve their omni-modal AI models, educators can assess the capabilities of AI models in learning environments, and content creators can utilize the evaluation results to enhance multimedia applications.	https://upload.wikimedia.