ea06a7c8-229e-43df-bcf8-3793166e16a0	PhaseContrast Imaging Solutions	To enhance the diagnostic capabilities of medical imaging through advanced phase-contrast tomography, offering superior imaging quality for the analysis of biological samples.	Conventional X-ray imaging techniques often struggle with soft tissue differentiation due to low contrast and high noise levels. Current systems may expose patients to higher radiation doses while lacking precision in depicting complex biological structures, especially in breast imaging.	Development and implementation of phase-contrast computed tomography (PB-CT) systems for biomedical applications, particularly breast cancer diagnostics. Integration with existing medical imaging infrastructure and optimization of imaging protocols to reduce radiation exposure.	["Radiologists","Oncologists","Medical Imaging Departments","Healthcare Providers"]	The system utilizes propagation-based phase-contrast imaging to create high-resolution 3D images of biological tissues. It operates through a sequence of steps: X-rays interact with biological samples, causing phase shifts that convey additional information not captured in traditional imaging. The system leverages advanced algorithms for image reconstruction, enhancing signal-to-noise ratios and spatial resolution while minimizing radiation dose.	Input Module: Receives X-ray images from the photon-counting detector. Image Processing Module: Applies phase retrieval algorithms and TIE-Hom operations to enhance image quality. Reconstruction Module: Utilizes various algorithms to reconstruct 3D distribution of refractive index for the sample based on collected projections. Output & Reporting Module: Generates high-resolution 3D images and diagnostic reports, integrating with existing medical record systems.	The integration of phase-contrast tomography with advanced noise resolution enhancement techniques allows for improved differentiation of soft tissues. By applying the Transport of Intensity Equation (TIE), the technique enhances imaging quality metrics significantly, providing high contrast with reduced radiation dosage compared to conventional CT imaging.	Enhancing the efficacy of imaging in radiology departments for breast cancer diagnostics, enabling better visualization of tumor margins and soft tissues. It can also facilitate remote diagnostics in telemedicine applications and provide high-quality imaging support in medical research.	\N	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.20277", "title": "PhaseContrast Imaging Solutions"}]	{"University of Melbourne","Monash University","University of Canterbury","University of New England","Australian Synchrotron"}
f300a406-76eb-4d70-80d0-e868cfba7694	Muon Diagnostic Imaging System	Enhance the diagnosis of structural integrity in concrete through high-resolution imaging techniques using muon tomography and deep learning.	Current structural diagnostic techniques for concrete suffer from limitations in penetrating dense materials and achieving high resolution, leading to potentially unsafe infrastructures due to undetected internal defects. Traditional methods such as ground-penetrating radar and ultrasound are often ineffective for deep concrete structures, highlighting the necessity for a more effective diagnostic tool.	Implementation of muon tomography integrated with deep learning for real-time diagnostics of reinforced concrete structures. Focus on detecting embedded metallic reinforcements and potential defects.	["Civil engineering firms","Municipal infrastructure managers","Construction companies","Non-destructive testing laboratories","Research institutions"]	The system utilizes muon particles generated from cosmic rays, which penetrate concrete structures. By detecting the deflections of these particles as they pass through materials of varying density, the system constructs a detailed image representation of the internal structure. Advanced deep learning models, specifically U-Net architectures, are trained to enhance image resolution and minimize noise, significantly reducing the required muon events for meaningful imaging.	Input Layer: Receives muon detection data from sensors. Preprocessing Module: Filters and normalizes the signal data from muon detectors. Feature Extraction: Uses data from muon tracks to generate pixel representations of the concrete structure. Neural Network (U-Net with RRDB): Processes feature maps to reconstruct high-resolution images, incorporating skip connections for effective feature reuse. Output Layer: Delivers visualized images indicating locations of steel reinforcements and structural anomalies.	Integration of Geant4 simulations with deep learning models to drastically improve image resolution and reduce data acquisition time. Introduction of data augmentation techniques to enhance training datasets. Utilization of neural network architectures specifically designed for low-signal environments, allowing for high-quality imaging from limited muon events.	Non-invasive structural diagnostics of concrete infrastructures, such as bridges, tunnels, and historical buildings, to assess internal conditions and prevent catastrophic failures. Application in regular maintenance and safety checks of civil engineering structures without disrupting public access.	\N	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.03339", "title": "Muon Diagnostic Imaging System"}]	{"STAP Reabilitação Estrutural","Politecnico di Torino",CERN,"Istituto Nazionale di Fisica Nucleare"}
