b8a78126-a0e8-410c-8705-4d5280dd2fef	TBHubbardDB	To provide a comprehensive database of tight-binding and extended Hubbard model electronic structure data for metal-organic frameworks (MOFs) to accelerate material discovery and design.	Existing databases of metal-organic frameworks lack sufficient electronic structure data, making it challenging to perform high-throughput computational screening and machine-learning-based design processes. The absence of reliable Hubbard parameters complicates evaluations of electronic interactions and correlations in MOFs, impeding advancements in developing new materials with desirable properties.	Creation of a database with tight-binding representations for approximately 10,000 MOFs and Extended Hubbard model parameters for 240 transition metal-containing MOFs. The database includes electronic structure data accessible for machine learning and quantum computing tasks.	["Material scientists","Quantum computing researchers","Chemists","Chemical engineers","Catalysis researchers"]	The database aggregates electronic structure data for MOFs derived from density functional theory (DFT) calculations. Specifically, a tight-binding Hamiltonian representation for each MOF is generated using PAOFLOW, and self-consistent Hubbard parameters are computed for a subset of materials. The dataset includes representative structural and electronic properties, and correlations can be explored by leveraging both tight-binding embeddings and SOAP descriptors in machine learning frameworks.	The architecture consists of the following components: 1. **Input Data Layer**: Contains structural data from the QMOF database. 2. **DFT Calculation Module**: Executes ground-state calculations for electronic structures using Quantum Espresso. 3. **Tight-binding Projection Module**: Uses PAOFLOW to map electronic structure data onto tight-binding Hamiltonians. 4. **Hubbard Parameter Calculation Module**: Computes U and V parameters for selected MOFs. 5. **Data Output Layer**: Stores the complete database in JSON format, along with auxiliary scripts for generating datasets and visualizations.	The TBHubbardDB uniquely combines extensive electronic structure data with both a standard tight-binding and extended Hubbard model framework, enabling advanced machine learning applications and fostering inverse design methodologies. It provides a structured representation of electronic interactions, while integrating SOAP descriptors to enhance predictive models.	Facilitating accelerated discovery of new metal-organic frameworks suitable for catalytic applications, carbon capture, or gas storage by utilizing high-throughput screening supported by reliable electronic structure data.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/b/b9/NUS_coat_of_arms.svg/260px-NUS_coat_of_arms.svg.png	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2503.12554", "title": "TBHubbardDB"}]	{"IBM Research, São Paulo","IBM Research Europe, Zurich","National Center for Competence in Research-Catalysis, Zurich","IBM Research, Rio de Janeiro","IBM Quantum, San Jose","IBM T.J. Watson Research Center, Yorktown Heights"}
23174691-4f4d-4d96-bde7-21d376582619	NanoRad Enhance	To optimize and enhance the effectiveness of radiotherapy through the application of gold nanoparticles for cancer treatment, using advanced analytical modeling techniques.	Current radiotherapy techniques may underutilize the potential enhancements provided by radiosensitizing agents like gold nanoparticles, leading to suboptimal treatment outcomes. Existing models fail to provide a reliable, quantitative approach for predicting enhancement based on nanoparticle concentration and beam quality.	Development of a predictive analytical model (σ-LEM) for determining the dose enhancement ratio (DER) in response to various concentrations of AuNPs during X-ray irradiation in cancer therapy.	["Oncology researchers","Radiotherapy clinics","Medical physicists","Pharmaceutical developers"]	The σ-LEM model calculates the dose enhancement due to gold nanoparticles based on a log-normal distribution of energy deposition, taking into account nanoparticle volume, concentration, and beam quality. The model outputs DERs and survival curves for various concentrations, allowing practitioners to optimize treatment protocols.	Input Layer: Data for AuNP concentrations and X-ray beam characteristics. Calculation Module: The σ-LEM predictive model calculates enhancement ratios using derived equations and incorporates Gaussian averaging for statistical relevance. Output Module: Displays DER results and expected survival outcomes, with options for clinical integration.	The model provides closed-form expressions for survival fractions and DERs, adapting to low, mid, and high concentrations of AuNPs. Significantly, it distinguishes between linear and quadratic dose responses, enhancing mechanistic understanding of treatment effectiveness.	Used in radiotherapy settings to determine optimal concentrations of gold nanoparticles for patient-specific treatment planning, thereby increasing the efficacy of radiation doses while potentially minimizing