681b639e-ebf3-44d3-a1b3-e02f8ebc198a	GymPN	Facilitate optimal decision-making in process management systems through Deep Reinforcement Learning, accommodating partial observability and multiple decision types.	Traditional process management systems often rely on simple heuristics for task allocation, which can lead to inefficiencies. Existing decision-making frameworks struggle with scenarios where not all aspects of the process are observable and fail to support simultaneous decision-making in complex workflows.	Modeling and simulating business process decision-making scenarios, incorporating partial observability and multi-action transitions for resource allocation.	["Business process managers","Operations researchers","Software developers in process automation","AI researchers in decision systems"]	Users define business processes using the Action-Evolution Petri Net framework. Each process can be configured to hide certain state information, simulating partial observability. The system employs Deep Reinforcement Learning to train policies for optimal task assignments based on the visible state.	GymPN consists of three primary modules: a Simulator for modeling processes, a Gym Environment for interaction with reinforcement learning algorithms, and an Agent that implements the learning policy using a specified DRL algorithm (currently PPO).	GymPN introduces capabilities for modeling partially observable processes and handles multiple decision-making actions in a single workflow. This flexibility enables a more realistic representation of complicated business scenarios compared to earlier frameworks.	Use in automated decision-making systems where multiple resources need assignment in uncertain environments, such as manufacturing workflows, service task management, or IT service processes.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/67/Eindhoven_University_of_Technology_logo_new.svg/560px-Eindhoven_University_of_Technology_logo_new.svg.png	2025-06-26 04:00