e6662d4e-eac4-4d08-bf8c-48b646346432	CogGen	Transform programming video learning into interactive, adaptive experiences by utilizing generative AI tutor systems based on the Cognitive Apprenticeship framework.	Learners struggle to engage effectively with programming videos due to the lack of immediate feedback and interactive guidance. Existing video-based learning methods do not provide personalized support or sufficient scaffolding for novices, leading to high cognitive load and inefficiencies in learning programming concepts.	Interactive tutoring using programming videos segmented by learning goals. Implementation in programming education environments, providing personalized instruction and support through conversation with learners.	["Educators in programming disciplines","Students learning programming","EdTech companies focusing on online learning","Universities providing programming courses","Educational researchers studying learning technologies"]	CogGen segments programming videos into distinct learning goals, employing a conversational engine that uses the Cognitive Apprenticeship framework. It generates structured interactions using a Domain-Specific Language (DSL) derived from video content and tracks student progress with Bayesian Knowledge Tracing, allowing for personalized adaptive instruction.	The architecture consists of three main components: (1) a video segmentation module that organizes video content by learning goals, (2) an instructional prompt generator that creates tailored teaching plans based on the CogApp framework, and (3) a student modeling component that monitors learner progress and adjusts instruction accordingly using Bayesian Knowledge Tracing.	Integration of generative AI with the Cognitive Apprenticeship framework allows for personalized, grounded tutoring experiences. The unique use of student modeling, video segmentation, and structured prompting techniques differentiates CogGen from traditional video-based learning tools.	CogGen