0dfb4f25-7d62-4141-bca7-812ff0ae26ea	Deep RT Planner	To provide an efficient and precise framework for radiotherapy treatment planning using deep learning, integrating physics-guided principles to enhance dose conformity and protect organs at risk during cancer treatment.	Current radiotherapy planning methods can be slow and computationally intensive, often requiring substantial human expertise and time to adapt treatment plans for anatomical changes during ongoing treatment. This can lead to inefficient workflows and increased treatment times for patients.	Automation of radiotherapy treatment planning for various cancer types, initial focus on prostate cancer using VMAT. Incorporation of a two-stage training process that includes both supervised learning and physics-based guidance.	["Oncologists","Radiotherapy departments","Healthcare institutions","Medical physicists","AI in healthcare technology providers"]	The system utilizes deep learning architectures, specifically a 3D U-Net and UNETR, to predict treatment plans based on patient CT scans. The first stage trains the model using ground truth treatment parameters. In the second stage, physics-guided supervision from predicted dose distributions enhances the planning accuracy by aligning it with clinical objectives.	Input Processing: Patient CT scans and treatment structure sets are processed. 3D U-Net or UNETR model architectures predict MLC apertures and MU values for treatment plans. A second pipeline, the RT Dose Predictor, estimates the 3D dose distribution, which is then used to compute the final loss function for training.	Physics-guided deep learning combines clinical dosimetry with advanced neural network architectures to improve the quality and speed of radiotherapy planning. This approach reduces radiation exposure to organs at risk and supports real-time adaptation based on anatomical changes.	Implementation in clinical settings for rapid generation of treatment plans, providing oncologists with immediate and optimized plans in under a second, as opposed to current systems that require several minutes.	https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Amsterdamuniversitylogo.svg	2025-06-26 04:00:00+00	2025-06-26 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.19880", "title": "Deep RT Planner"}]	{"University of Amsterdam","Netherlands Cancer Institute"}
6c0e51b9-9e84-4077-942c-443d81cdad22	VoxelOpt	Enhance the efficiency and accuracy of deformable image registration in abdominal CT scans using voxel-adaptive message passing for discrete optimization.	Traditional methods for deformable image registration are often slow and computationally expensive, resulting in inefficiencies, particularly with large volumetric data. Learning-based approaches may lack accuracy without sufficient training data, and they underperform compared to iterative methods when label supervision is unavailable. There's a need for a solution that balances speed and accuracy effectively without relying heavily on labeled data.	Developed for deformable image registration in abdominal CT scans, VoxelOpt integrates with existing image analysis workflows to provide a faster, more accurate registration process. Its application extends to clinical settings where rapid and reliable image registration is crucial, without requiring extensive annotated datasets.	["Healthcare providers","Radiologists","Medical imaging software developers","Researchers in medical imaging","Hospitals and diagnostic centers"]	VoxelOpt processes fixed and moving images through a pre-trained foundational segmentation model to extract feature maps. It computes a 6D cost volume for displacement estimation using voxel-wise displacement entropy to guide message passing. The algorithm performs a discrete optimization approach with adaptive filtering of displacement signals, leading to efficient convergence in just a few iterations and yielding a precise displacement field.	VoxelOpt architecture consists of multiple modules: Feature Extraction Module (utilizing a pre-trained segmentation model), Cost Volume Calculation Module (computes 6D cost volumes), Displacement Entropy Calculation (measures voxel-wise displacement entropy), Adaptive Message Passing Module (adjusts information exchange based on signal strength), and Optimization Module (executes the discrete optimization to derive the final displacement field).	VoxelOpt introduces voxel-adaptive message passing which prioritizes displacement information based on voxel signal strength. It employs a multi-level image pyramid structure that avoids exponential growth in computation while maintaining accuracy, integrating features from pretrained models instead of relying on hand-crafted features or complex training processes.	Applicable in clinical radiology for efficient and accurate registration of abdominal CT images, enhancing diagnostic capabilities, facilitating telemedicine applications, and supporting research involving medical image analysis.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e4/Arms_of_University_of_Oxford.svg/500px-Arms_of_University_of_Oxford.svg.png	2025-06-26 04:00:00+00	2025-06-26 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.19975", "title": "VoxelOpt"}]	{"Cornell University","Hunan University","University of Oxford","Shanghai Jiao Tong University"}
332e8d34-9544-4e3a-bc60-a9741b662ac2	MIRAGE	To provide a robust benchmark for evaluating multimodal models in expert-level agricultural consultations, focusing on real-world, context-rich interactions that involve image-based queries and expert responses.	Current benchmarks do not accurately reflect the complexities of expert consultation interactions due to their reliance on well-defined queries and closed-set taxonomy. Farmers often face ambiguity and require expert guidance that incorporates visual evidence, yet models struggle with open-ended questions and reasoning under partial information.	Evaluation of vision-language models (VLMs) on multimodal tasks in agriculture, specifically focusing on crop health, pest diagnosis, and management advice through both single-turn and multi-turn dialogues that utilize real user-expert interactions.	["Agricultural researchers","AI developers in agriculture","Farmers and agricultural professionals","Agri-tech companies"]	MIRAGE includes curated datasets of over 35,000 expert-user interactions that combine natural language queries with images. Models utilize these datasets to learn from multimodal inputs and are evaluated on their ability to answer identification questions, manage queries and decide whether to clarify or respond during dialogue sequences. Each task focuses on identification and management through a cognitive reasoning framework that assesses the model's outputs for accuracy, relevance, and diagnostic parsimony.	The benchmark consists of two main components: MIRAGE-MMST (Multimodal Single-Turn) for evaluating individual dialogues and MIRAGE-MMMT (Multimodal Multi-Turn) for assessing interactive conversation abilities. Each includes data from actual conversations tracked in a structured format that incorporates image inputs, user queries, and expert responses.	Introduction of an interpretable ensemble of reasoning-capable LLMs (DeepSeek-R1-Distill, Qwen-3-32B, Phi-4-Reasoning) as judges for evaluation, moving beyond traditional single-model evaluations. The methodology enhances evaluation quality through multi-run assessments and provides detailed insights into model reasoning processes, improving transparency.	Supports the development of advanced AI assistants capable of providing accurate agricultural advice using multimodal data, thus enhancing decision-making in real farming scenarios and paving the way toward improved agricultural practices.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/af/University_of_Illinois_seal.svg/360px-University_of_Illinois_seal.svg.png	2025-06-26 04:00:00+00	2025-06-26 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.20100", "title": "MIRAGE"}]	{"University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign",Amazon}
2cf43b2c-32e5-4bb4-b5a2-61556c6d6ea6	MockLLM	To provide a collaborative framework for mock interviewing that enhances person-job matching processes by simulating adaptive dialogues between job seekers and recruiters.	Traditional online recruitment methods often rely on static analysis of resumes and job descriptions, which do not account for the dynamic interactions of interviews. Existing models lack the capability to simulate realistic interview scenarios and assess candidates in a conversational context, leading to suboptimal matching outcomes.	Generates mock interviews and evaluations between job seekers and recruiters in real-time. Facilitates two-sided feedback and evaluation for improved matching accuracy. Integrates reflection memory for adaptive learning from past interview interactions.	["Online recruitment platforms","HR agencies","Job seekers","Recruiters"]	MockLLM employs Large Language Models (LLMs) to simulate interviews. The model generates questions based on the job description and the candidate's resume, allowing multi-turn conversations. After the interview, both parties evaluate each other using a defined handshake protocol, determining mutual fit based on interview performance and historical interactions.	The framework consists of three core modules: 1) Mock Interview Generation - simulates interactive interviews; 2) Two-Sided Evaluation in Handshake Protocol - refines candidate evaluation through mutual feedback; 3) Reflection Memory Generation - allows continuous improvement of strategies based on past experiences. Each module communicates and shares data to enhance the overall matching process.	MockLLM introduces a unique multi-agent behavior collaboration paradigm where the interviewer and candidate roles can adapt and learn from interactions. It improves upon existing frameworks by integrating reflection memory and dynamic strategy modifications, setting it apart from traditional static recruitment models.	Hiring platforms can utilize MockLLM to produce enhanced candidate profiles through realistic mock interviews, leading to better hiring decisions. Job seekers can improve their interviewing skills and receive customized feedback, thus becoming more competitive in the job market.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/64/University_of_the_Chinese_Academy_of_Sciences_logo.svg/500px-University_of_the_Chinese_Academy_of_Sciences_logo.svg.png	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2405.18113", "title": "MockLLM"}]	{"Hongda Sun, Renmin University of China","Hongzhan Lin, Ministry of Education","Haiyu Yan, University of Chinese Academy of Sciences","Yang Song, BOSS Zhipin","Xin Gao, King Abdullah University","Rui Yan, Renmin University of China"}
f2ef1d06-cfcd-4f80-8111-ef23bd902c3f	PRG Visual Insights	Enhance visual representation learning by harnessing the power of pretrained reversible generative models to deliver robust feature extraction for a variety of discriminative tasks.	Existing generative models excel in generation but have been underutilized in feature extraction, leading to subpar performance in discriminative tasks such as image classification. Traditional approaches often lack generalizability and robustness due to reliance on specific model architectures or features.	Unsupervised visual representation learning, applicable to various tasks such as image classification, object detection, and anomaly detection across different data types and formats.	["AI researchers","Data scientists","Tech companies","Educational institutions","Software developers"]	The system begins by pretraining a reversible generative model on a large dataset to extract high-quality features. These representations are then fine-tuned for specific downstream tasks by reversing the generative process. Features can be extracted from multiple levels of the generative model's latent space, adapting flexibly to the task requirements and maximizing the performance of classification or detection algorithms.	Input Layer: Accepts raw images. Pretraining Module: Utilizes continuous-time stochastic flow models to learn representation through the generative process. Fine-tuning Module: Reverses the generative model to extract meaningful features for specific tasks, utilizing shared parameters. Classification Layer: A simple Multi-Layer Perceptron for classification based on the features extracted from the reverse process. Output Layer: Provides predictions with associated probabilities.	Model-agnostic feature extraction method, leveraging the reversible nature of generative models. Capable of seamlessly integrating various architectures (U-Net, Transformers). Achieves high-performance representation learning without requiring access to internal features, offering a two-stage pretraining-fine-tuning paradigm that enhances efficiency and performance.	Image classification in healthcare, fine-tuning pretrained models on new datasets with minimal data to maximize classification accuracy. Integration in AI product development for improved visual understanding across images.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/0/09/CUHK_Coat_of_Arms.png	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2412.01787", "title": "PRG Visual Insights"}]	{"School of Automation Science and Engineering, Xi’an Jiaotong University","Shanghai Artificial Intelligence Laboratory","The Chinese University of Hong Kong","SenseTime Research"}
8cfe2940-165e-4c5f-9872-d5f0ff05fc14	SIDA	To provide an extensive solution for detecting, localizing, and explaining deepfakes in social media images, enhancing trust in digital content.	The rapid generation of realistic synthetic images leads to misinformation and erodes trust in digital content. Existing detection methods lack comprehensiveness and are often limited to facial images, leaving a gap in solutions for social media contexts where manipulations can be subtle and diverse.	Detection, localization, and explanation of deepfake images on social media platforms. The project includes the creation of a diverse dataset (SID-Set) and the development of a deepfake detection framework (SIDA).	["Social media platforms","Content moderators","Digital journalism organizations","Legal and compliance teams","AI research and development industries"]	The SIDA framework consists of a large vision-language model that processes images along with textual prompts. It utilizes features extracted from both the visual and language domains to determine the authenticity of images. If tampered, SIDA generates masks for the altered regions and provides textual explanations for its detections.	The architecture includes a large vision-language model with multiple components: an input layer for images and text prompts, a detection head for identifying image types (real, synthetic, tampered), and a segmentation module for creating masks of tampered areas. It integrates feature extraction, attention mechanisms, and layers to enhance detection performance.	SIDA introduces a new dataset (SID-Set) comprising 300K images specifically tailored for social media deepfake detection. It leverages significant advancements in large vision-language models to not only detect but also localize and explain manipulations, setting a new standard in the field.	SIDA can be utilized by content moderators on social media to quickly identify and understand deepfakes in order to prevent misinformation dissemination. It also aids digital journalists in verifying image authenticity during reporting.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/f8/Nanyang_Technological_University_coat_of_arms_vector.svg/280px-Nanyang_Technological_University_coat_of_arms_vector.svg.png	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2412.04292", "title": "SIDA"}]	{"University of Liverpool","Nanyang Technological University","WMG, University of Warwick","The Chinese University of Hong Kong, Shenzhen"}
edd1156f-082c-4fa8-8640-b7080c56a519	Energy Match AI	Integrate energy-based modeling with flow matching techniques to enhance generative modeling and inverse problem solving across various industries.	Current generative models have limitations in effectively handling partial observations and incorporating additional priors. Many approaches do not efficiently learn the underlying data distributions, leading to subpar performance on sample generation and inverse problems. A robust solution is needed to effectively bridge these gaps.	Generative modeling of complex data distributions for various applications including image generation, protein design, and inverse problems across multiple domains.	["Research institutions","Biotechnology companies","Pharmaceutical industries","AI development teams"]	The Energy Match AI framework utilizes a combined approach where samples are transported from a noise distribution to a target data distribution via a scalar potential field. This framework enhances sample diversity near data manifolds and employs Langevin dynamics for refinement of generated samples, allowing for precise control over quality and diversity.	The system comprises a neural network-based architecture that integrates a UNet model for feature extraction and a transformer module for understanding complex data relationships. The learned scalar potential field directs frequent flow-like transport, transitioning into Langevin dynamics as samples near the data manifold.	Energy Match AI introduces a unique two-regime training strategy and utilizes a single, time-independent scalar potential to improve sampling speed and fidelity. This approach merges the strengths of energy-based models with flow matching, resulting in high-quality generative outputs with a manageable complexity.	Applications include high-fidelity image generation for research purposes, controlled protein design in biotechnology, and efficient solutions for inverse problems in data science and computational biology.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/99/ETH_Z%C3%BCrich_Logo_black.svg/500px-ETH_Z%C3%BCrich_Logo_black.svg.png	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2504.10612", "title": "Energy Match AI"}]	{"University of Zurich","ETH Zurich","Harvard University","Technical University of Munich"}
762ceef4-9c1d-46ce-8322-2da061e3e2b6	AutoRefine AI	Enhance the reasoning capabilities of large language models by implementing a search-and-refine approach that filters, distills, and organizes relevant knowledge for more accurate answer generation.	Current retrieval-augmented reasoning models struggle with synthesizing and refining information from retrieved documents, leading to inaccuracies in responses, especially in multi-hop reasoning tasks. Traditional methods focus purely on retrieval without any systematic refinement, resulting in the inclusion of irrelevant and noisy information in answers.	Incorporate a search-and-refine methodology into LLMs for augmented reasoning across various QA tasks, including single-hop and multi-hop question answering. Integration with existing knowledge retrieval systems to provide timely and accurate responses.	["AI developers","Research institutions","Tech companies","Educational platforms","Information services"]	AutoRefine operates by taking a user query and processing it through a series of steps: First, the model 'thinks' about the query to assess what it knows; second, it performs a 'search' to retrieve relevant documents; third, it 'refines' the information by distilling key points from the retrieved data; and finally, it generates an 'answer' based on the refined knowledge. This iteratively allows for improved document selection and utilization.	AutoRefine consists of four main modules: Thinking Module (assesses the query), Search Module (queries an external knowledge base), Refinement Module (distills retrieved documents), and Answer Module (generates a response). Each module communicates to iteratively improve the quality of the final answer through reinforcement learning.	The introduction of a 'search-and-refine-during-think' paradigm that encourages intermediate refinement steps in the reasoning loop, utilizing both answer correctness rewards and retrieval-specific rewards, significantly improving the quality of multi-hop reasoning in LLMs.	Incorporating AutoRefine into existing AI systems to enhance performance in complex question answering, enabling applications such as virtual assistants, automated research tools, and educational software that require nuanced understanding and synthesis of information.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/3/3c/Logo_of_University_of_Science_and_Technology_of_China.svg/300px-Logo_of_University_of_Science_and_Technology_of_China.svg.png	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.11277", "title": "AutoRefine AI"}]	{"University of Science and Technology of China","National University of Singapore","DP Technology"}
965c87c0-d9d3-4587-83c1-43db89f021d7	SmoothSinger	To create high-quality and expressive singing voice synthesis using an end-to-end conditional diffusion model that minimizes audio artifacts and enhances naturalness.	Existing singing voice synthesis models often rely on two-stage architectures that introduce distortion during waveform reconstruction. This reduces audio fidelity and expressiveness, necessitating improved methods for generating smooth and natural singing voices.	End-to-end singing voice synthesis from musical scores, including lyrics and pitch, through a unified diffusion model. It aims to eliminate the need for separate vocoders while ensuring high audio quality and expressiveness.	["Music producers","Game developers","Content creators","AI musicians","Record labels"]	SmoothSinger processes input conditions (lyrics and musical score) through pretrained models to generate reference audio. It utilizes a conditional diffusion model with dual branches to denoise and synthesize high-fidelity audio directly, while training involves the use of degraded audio to enhance model robustness.	SmoothSinger features a dual-branch architecture with a Diffusion module for denoising and a Reference module that processes acoustic features from reference audio. It incorporates a Multi-Resolution (MR) module for capturing low-frequency characteristics. Overall, it employs a U-Net-inspired design for processing audio at various resolutions.	The proposed model eliminates the need for a separate vocoder, integrating denoising directly within the framework. Its unique reference-based feature extraction enhances expressiveness and coherence, while the multi-resolution approach improves fidelity and captures varied frequency structures effectively.	Smart music applications generating realistic singing voices for virtual characters, productive tools for songwriters, and advanced music synthesis engines in gaming and film soundtracks.	\N	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:0