78e64b22-33d1-449e-9025-f64f05308a89	Quantum Circuit Parameterization Accelerator	To enhance the efficiency of executing parameterized quantum circuits through a hardware-software co-design that minimizes classical bottlenecks.	Current quantum circuit execution often faces classical overhead during compilation and loading phases, which limits the speed and scalability of quantum computations. Many circuits have structural equivalency, making it inefficient to compile each circuit independently.	Integration of parameterized circuit execution techniques into existing quantum computing frameworks, reducing compilation times and classical processing overhead for various quantum protocols.	["Quantum computing researchers","Quantum hardware developers","Software engineers in quantum computing"]	The system utilizes a unique Read-Identify-Peel (RIP) process to analyze a batch of quantum circuits, identify structurally-equivalent circuits, and peel parameters before executing on FPGA. The parameters are stitched back in real-time to run the circuit using the Deft scheduler.	The architecture consists of a host computer running RIP software and a hardware component on an FPGA with a Stitch module. The Deft scheduler manages orchestrating circuit execution while interacting with the QubiC quantum control system for dynamic parameter control.	The integration of RIP and Stitch allows for real-time parameter binding during execution, significantly minimizing the compilation overhead. The design applies to structurally-equivalent circuits across various quantum protocols, providing substantial speedup.	This technology enhances the execution of randomized benchmarking and cycle benchmarking protocols, speeding up the overall quantum circuit execution by reducing classical time spent on compilation and loading.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/b/b9/NUS_coat_of_arms.svg/260px-NUS_coat_of_arms.svg.png	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.