ec977b4e-b51a-4535-95ff-3021790f3c96	MoSi2N4 FET Innovators	To develop and optimize high-performance field-effect transistors (FETs) using the MoSi2N4 material family for the advancement of next-generation CMOS technology at the ˚Angstr"om scale.	Conventional silicon-based transistors are approaching physical limits, leading to performance degradation in devices below 10 nm. This necessitates the exploration of alternative materials and architectures that can maintain efficiency and performance in ultra-scaled electronics.	Design and simulation of MoSi2N4 family FETs leveraging computational methods for performance optimization, aimed at the sub-10nm node. This includes investigation into dielectric materials and electrical contact optimization for practical applications.	["Semiconductor manufacturers","Electronics companies","Research institutions","University technology transfer offices"]	Utilizes first-principles density functional theory (DFT) in combination with nonequilibrium Green's function (NEGF) transport simulations to model and predict the characteristics of MoSi2N4 FETs. The device architecture is designed to suppress short-channel effects while enabling better gate control and carrier injection through optimized metal contacts.	The device consists of a MoSi2N4 monolayer as the channel, integrated with high-k dielectrics and advanced metal contacts. The simulation framework utilizes NEGF for transport characteristics and DFT for electronic structure calculations, facilitating a deep understanding of performance metrics under various conditions.	Explores the unique properties of the MoSi2N4 material family to achieve superior carrier mobility and ability to form efficient n-type and p-type contacts. Additionally, it incorporates advanced design techniques such as underlap structures and edge-passivation strategies to enhance performance.	Develop high-performance, low-power transistors suitable for integration into ultra-dense circuits, thus supporting the transition to the ˚Angstr"om-era of electronics characterized by improved efficiency and reduced thermionic leakage.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f4/Peking_University_seal.svg/500px-Peking_University_seal.svg.png	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.21366", "title": "MoSi2N4 FET Innovators"}]	{"Singapore University of Technology and Design","Peking University","National University of Singapore","A*STAR Research Institutes"}
c2048485-69e2-4de7-88f3-24792f7c4f4d	Plasma Dynamics Optimizer	Enhance the understanding and manipulation of magnetic fields in helical plasma systems through accurate modeling of the α and β coefficients under turbulence conditions.	Current methods of analyzing plasma dynamics in astrophysical systems often lack precision and fail to account for the complex interactions between turbulent motions and magnetic field generation. The lack of understanding of the influence of turbulence on magnetic diffusivity leads to inefficiencies in both observational and experimental setups.	Development of a comprehensive modeling software framework aimed at accurately predicting magnetic field behavior in helical plasma systems subject to turbulent flow. This includes integration with existing observational data and simulation tools.	["Astrophysicists","Plasma physicists","Research institutions","University laboratories"]	The software utilizes advanced algorithms to compute the α and β coefficients from large-scale magnetic field data obtained from simulations or experimental setups. By applying the principles derived from the research, it simulates the dynamics of magnetic fields in plasma under varying Reynolds numbers and magnetic Prandtl numbers, providing real-time insights into the turbulence and dynamo processes.	1. Data Input Module: Receives magnetic field and kinetic energy data from experiments or simulations. 2. Parameter Calculation Engine: Computes α and β using statistical and numerical methods. 3. Simulation Module: Runs simulations of helical plasma behavior incorporating the computed coefficients. 4. Visualization and Reporting Interface: Displays results through user-friendly visualizations, including graphs and charts showing magnetic field evolution and turbulence interactions.	The focus on integrating turbulent kinetic data to derive negative magnetic diffusivity coefficients represents a significant advancement over conventional modeling approaches. It allows for more accurate predictions of magnetic field behavior in situations where traditional models falter, particularly in highly turbulent environments.	Application in astrophysical research to improve predictions of solar magnetic activity and better understand processes such as solar flares that are influenced by turbulent plasma interactions.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/a/a4/Seal_of_the_California_Institute_of_Technology.svg/300px-Seal_of_the_California_Institute_of_Technology.svg.png	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2410.19232", "title": "Plasma Dynamics Optimizer"}]	{"Institute of Plasmas Turbulence and Magnetic Fields, Soongsil University","California Institute of Technology","NASA Jet Propulsion Laboratory"}
94e10eb1-ece2-46b0-a22a-ec01abfd392d	Brain2Model Transfer (B2M)	Enhance the training of artificial neural networks by leveraging human brain neural activity as a teacher to improve sensory and decision-making models.	Current artificial models require extensive computational resources and large data sets to learn effectively. They often lack the efficiency demonstrated by the human brain, which can learn complex representations from minimal data. This poses limitations for applications that demand rapid adaptation and real-time decision-making.	Utilizing human neural activity data to train AI models across various tasks such as memory-based decision making and scene reconstruction for autonomous driving. This includes integration with machine learning frameworks to facilitate faster convergence and higher predictive accuracy.	["AI Researchers","Autonomous Vehicle Developers","Cognitive Neuroscientists","Healthcare Technology Companies"]	B2M employs two primary strategies—Brain Contrastive Transfer and Brain Latent Transfer. The system collects neural data while humans perform specific tasks and uses this information to train artificial neural networks through specialized loss functions that align neural embeddings with model representations. This allows the AI to learn more efficiently by mimicking the learning dynamics of the human brain.	The B2M framework consists of input layers for neural data, preprocessors for standardizing the data, a feature extraction module that produces embeddings both from human brain activity and from the AI model, a contrastive learning mechanism for aligning these embeddings, and a main model that incorporates the adjusted loss functions for effective training. It includes variants for recurrent neural networks and variational autoencoders based on the task at hand.	The B2M framework introduces the novel integration of human neural data into AI training processes, allowing for more efficient learning from less data, while the contrastive alignment process enables a mutual information maximization between brain and model embeddings. This innovation can transform how AI adapts to complex tasks and environments, leveraging insights from human cognitive behavior.	Enhanced accuracy and efficiency in decision-making in robotics and autonomous systems through rapid adaptation and improved sensitivity to environmental cues, as seen in memory-based tasks and real-time scene processing for driving applications.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b0/Columbia_coat_of_arms_no_crest.svg/500px-Columbia_coat_of_arms_no_crest.svg.png	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.20834", "title": "Brain2Model Transfer (B2M)"}]	{"Columbia University","Baylor College of Medicine"}
716ef32e-2a08-45c0-a588-e84535821148	Unlasting	Enhance the prediction of single-cell responses under various genetic and molecular perturbations, enabling better understanding of gene functions and improving drug screening processes through advanced machine learning techniques.	Single-cell sequencing is destructive and prevents capturing the same cell's phenotype before and after perturbations. As a result, data collected for unperturbed and perturbed conditions are unpaired, leading to challenges in accurately predicting cellular responses under novel scenarios. Existing models often address this issue inadequately by either assuming forced pairings or neglecting the relationships between unperturbed and perturbed states.	Estimation of single-cell gene expression profiles under different perturbation conditions (both genetic and molecular) using a novel dual conditional diffusion approach. Integration with existing gene regulatory networks for enhanced interpretability and biological relevance.	["Biotech companies","Pharmaceutical companies","Academic researchers in genomics","Healthcare institutions","Data scientists specializing in biology"]	The Unlasting model employs Dual Diffusion Implicit Bridges (DDIB) to learn the latent distributions of unperturbed and perturbed cells. It includes a source model that learns unperturbed cell distributions and a target model that generates predictions under perturbation based on a shared prior space. Gene regulatory network (GRN) information is integrated for meaningful signal propagation, and a masking mechanism predicts silent genes, enhancing prediction quality.	The model comprises two main components—source and target models. Both share similar architectures, employing GRN blocks for gene interaction modeling. The source model learns the distribution of unperturbed gene expressions, while the target model utilizes perturbation information to model responses under various conditions. The architecture leverages multi-layer perceptrons for data encoding, with dedicated mask models for gene silencing prediction integrated into the framework.	Unlasting advances the field by effectively modeling unpaired data through DDIB, providing a biologically grounded approach to predict cellular responses. The innovative use of gene regulatory networks for context-aware signal propagation alongside a dedicated mask model to address gene silencing enhances the model's capacity to capture the heterogeneity in single-cell responses under perturbations. It also introduces new evaluation metrics tailored for single-cell perturbation data.	The project can be applied in drug discovery processes to forecast cellular reactions to new drug candidates, enhance gene function studies through CRISPR perturbations, and support personalized medicine initiatives by predicting individual cellular responses to therapeutic agents.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/1/16/Zhejiang_University_Logo.svg/360px-Zhejiang_University_Logo.svg.png	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.21107", "title": "Unlasting"}]	{"Zhejiang University","AI Lab, Westlake University","The Hong Kong University of Science and Technology"}
632f3ef2-20e0-43f5-adb6-d956fec63c3c	PARALLELPROMPT	To identify and leverage latent semantic parallelism in large language model queries to improve inference efficiency while maintaining semantic fidelity.	Most LLM serving systems treat prompts as single, monolithic inputs and do not exploit the potential for parallel execution within a single query. This results in suboptimal execution times and unnecessary latency when tasks could be processed in parallel.	Benchmarking intra-query parallelism, identifying parallelizable structures in natural language prompts, and providing tools to implement these insights in LLM serving systems.	["AI researchers","LLM developers","Tech companies utilizing LLMs","Data scientists"]	The system extracts structured schemas from real user prompts that indicate task decomposition into independent subtasks. It then compares execution times between serial and parallel processing for identified prompts to measure improvements in speed and quality.	The architecture consists of a schema extraction module that uses a trained model to analyze user prompts, identify potential subtasks, and create structured templates. A parallel execution engine handles the independent execution of these tasks, measuring outputs against serial execution for performance evaluations.	The introduction of a comprehensive benchmark for intra-query parallelism that utilizes real-world user prompts and provides a systematic approach to exposing latent parallelism for efficiency gains in LLM query processing.	Utilizing the benchmark and tools to optimize the processing of user queries in real-time applications, such as chatbots and virtual assistants, by reducing latencies and improving the throughput of responses.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/b/bb/Carnegie_Mellon_University_seal.svg/300px-Carnegie_Mellon_University_seal.svg.png	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.18728", "title": "PARALLELPROMPT"}]	{"Carnegie Mellon University","Stanford University"}
29934c84-5a37-463e-8dce-9e4d215c4995	sPoRT (Sequential Positivity Regression Tree)	Enhance the robustness and interpretability of causal inference by identifying and addressing sequential positivity violations in longitudinal studies.	Causal inference methods relying on sequential positivity assumptions often encounter challenges due to the complex structure of longitudinal data. Verifying these assumptions is typically cumbersome, requiring multiple parametric models that may not be accurately specified, leading to identification bias and diminished reliability of findings.	Provision of a computational tool (sPoRT) that assesses and identifies violations of the sequential positivity assumption in longitudinal data, applicable across various types of treatments and data structures. Support for both static and dynamic treatment rules is included.	["Epidemiologists","Statisticians","Data Scientists","Clinical Researchers","Public Health Officials"]	The sPoRT algorithm employs regression tree models to identify subgroups of individuals that lack sufficient data support for specific interventions across multiple time points. The algorithm provides interpretable output that allows users to understand the nature of positivity violations and suggests adjustments for treatment strategies based on identified subgroups.	The system architecture consists of the following components: Data Input Module for longitudinal datasets; Preprocessing Pipeline for data cleaning and transformation; sPoRT Algorithm Core which applies regression trees to identify positivity violations; Output Module providing visual interpretations and subgroup analyses; User Interface for interaction with the algorithm, parameter setting, and visualization of results.	sPoRT introduces a robust methodology for evaluating sequential positivity using regression trees, which allow for the identification of subgroups without strong parametric assumptions. The algorithm adapts dynamically to the data structure, facilitating analysis with static or dynamic treatments, and improving interpretability of results through its tree-based approach.	Applied to longitudinal studies evaluating pediatric antiretroviral therapy (ART) initiation rules where traditional positivity checks failed, enabling health professionals to make informed decisions about treatment strategy based on the identified violations.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c5/Shield_of_Imperial_College_London.svg/330px-Shield_of_Imperial_College_London.svg.png	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2412.10245", "title": "sPoRT (Sequential Positivity Regression Tree)"}]	{"Université de Montréal","Ludwig-Maximilians University Munich","University of Cape Town","University of Granada","London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine","Jewish General Hospital","McGill University"}
b993e24d-4ca8-4fbf-bac4-58f64970e3a6	Entanglement Certifier	To provide a reliable certification method for the Schmidt number of bipartite quantum states, enabling efficient use of high-dimensional entangled states in various quantum information applications.	Traditional methods for certifying the Schmidt number of quantum states rely heavily on measurement devices, which can be imperfect and lead to faulty results. There is a need for a more robust and reliable certification method that minimizes dependency on such devices.	Certification of Schmidt number for bipartite quantum states, employing measurement-device-independent methods to ensure accuracy even in the presence of potentially flawed measurement devices.	["Quantum physicists","Quantum computing researchers","Quantum cryptography experts","Quantum communication specialists"]	The system implements a semi-quantum nonlocal game framework where Alice and Bob each receive trusted quantum inputs corresponding to their quantum states. They perform joint measurements on these states using classical outputs, from which correlation statistics are generated. By analyzing these correlations against predetermined thresholds, the system can certify whether the Schmidt number of the shared state exceeds a specified value.	1. Quantum Inputs: Alice and Bob receive trusted quantum states. 2. Measurement Devices: Alice and Bob perform measurements on these states, treated as black boxes. 3. Correlation Module: Generates correlations based on measurement outcomes to assess Schmidt number. 4. Certification Module: Evaluates correlations against Schmidt number thresholds using optimized witness operators.	Utilization of measurement-device-independent semi-quantum nonlocal games allows certification without relying on potentially faulty measurement devices. This method ensures robust certification of Schmidt numbers, particularly for all entangled states, overcoming limitations of previous approaches.	Experimental validation of high-dimensional entangled states for quantum cryptography and communication applications, ensuring that states used in protocols meet necessary entanglement criteria.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/b/b9/NUS_coat_of_arms.svg/260px-NUS_coat_of_arms.svg.png	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.13296", "title": "Entanglement Certifier"}]	{"S. N. Bose National Centre for Basic Sciences","European Quantum Technologies Consortium","Quantum Information Science Institute"}
7dccb563-8ac3-43dc-9ec9-776e546185b9	xChemAgents	Integrate physics-aware reasoning within multimodal property prediction to enhance predictive accuracy while ensuring interpretability in quantum chemistry applications.	Current machine learning methods in quantum chemistry often struggle with interpretability and can be sensitive to the excessive dimensionality of data. Despite advancements, existing tools may not provide reliable insights or meet the stringent physical constraints necessary for accurate molecular property predictions.	Predictive modeling of molecular properties using a combination of geometric and textual descriptors. Focus on enhancing feature selection processes, providing transparent rationale, and adhering to physics-based constraints in predictions.	["Chemistry researchers","Materials scientists","Pharmaceutical industries","Academic institutions"]	xChemAgents utilizes a cooperative agent framework comprising a Selector and a Validator. The Selector identifies a sparse selection of relevant descriptors from a descriptor set and assigns normalized weights, providing reasoning for its choices. The Validator assesses these selections against physical principles (unit consistency, scaling laws) and either approves them or gives feedback for refinement. This iterative process culminates in a validated descriptor set, which is subsequently integrated into a graph neural network (GNN) model for accurate property predictions.	The architecture consists of two main components: the Selector agent functioning as a chemistry-tuned language model for feature selection, and the Validator agent enforcing physical constraints via iterative dialogue. Both outputs are merged with geometric representations of molecules before being processed by a GNN surrogate model.	The integration of agentic AI for cooperative reasoning allows for a streamlined feature selection process that incorporates multilevel physical constraints. This approach enhances both accuracy and transparency in molecular property predictions while reducing the dependency on large descriptor pools.	The system can be applied for efficient virtual screening in drug discovery, enabling researchers to swiftly identify promising molecular candidates while providing understandable rationales for predictions.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/Logo_of_the_Technical_University_of_Munich.svg/360px-Logo_of_the_Technical_University_of_Munich.svg.png	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.20574", "title": "xChemAgents"}]	{"Texas A&M University","Istanbul Technical University","Hamad Bin Khalifa University","Ankara University"}
e9b05fb7-260a-413d-8260-139c271b4cbe	RefExpress AI	Facilitate advanced visual information retrieval and object localization using natural language queries, enabling seamless interaction between users and images.	Many existing solutions separate image retrieval and object localization, requiring either a two-step process or lacking effective search mechanisms. Users often need to identify specific objects based on detailed language descriptions across large image galleries, where previous solutions fell short in accommodating complex expressions and efficient searches.	Instance-level retrieval and localization from extensive image galleries, enhancing vision-language models to interpret and respond to intricate natural language queries.	["E-commerce platforms","Security surveillance systems","Digital asset management tools","Social media platforms"]	RefExpress AI utilizes the CLARE model to process textual queries and visual content concurrently. The textual branch encodes detailed descriptions into embeddings, while the visual branch extracts features from images. These embeddings are then matched to identify the correct objects within the gallery accurately, achieving both retrieval and localization.	The system features a dual-stream architecture: the textual stream is responsible for generating embeddings from user queries and enriching them with relational context using the Mix of Relation Experts (MORE). The visual stream concurrently processes image data to extract instance-level features. A contrastive learning objective, defined as Contrastive Language-Instance Alignment (CLIA), aligns both modalities effectively, allowing for real-time retrieval and localization.	The integration of the MORE module allows for dynamic handling of relational expressions in queries. CLIA enhances the retrieval process by establishing a global comparison framework across image content, improving response accuracy significantly.	In an e-commerce environment, a user can input a detailed description like 'the blue dress with floral patterns displayed on a mannequin in the middle of the page,' and the system will quickly retrieve the relevant image showcasing that specific item and pinpoint its exact location.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/0/09/CUHK_Coat_of_Arms.png	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.18246", "title": "RefExpress AI"}]	{"Institute of Automation, Chinese Academy of Sciences","Mashang Consumer Finance Co, Ltd","Cloud Innovations Team"}
3832e13d-b2a1-4696-a7e3-1904e6d6ece5	CausalXray	Enhance the reliability and effectiveness of chest X-ray disease classification by leveraging causal representation learning with an observational grouping approach to ensure robustness across diverse patient demographics.	Traditional models trained on chest X-rays can rely on group-specific patterns, such as those influenced by sex or race, leading to inconsistent performance and health disparities. A solution is needed to ensure models are less biased and more reliable across diverse populations.	Development of a classification framework for chest X-ray images, focusing on improving model generalisability and robustness through causal representation learning. The framework will be tested across various demographic groups leveraging existing datasets such as CheXpert and MIMIC.	["Healthcare providers","Medical imaging companies","Radiologists","AI developers","Healthcare researchers"]	The solution utilizes an end-to-end framework that learns identifiable representations through causal representation learning combined with observational grouping. By grouping observations based on demographic attributes (race, sex, imaging views), it trains a feature extractor to produce invariant features which are then used for disease classification. The model optimizes an invariant loss alongside classification loss to ensure that it captures consistent, generalizable patterns across groups.	The system consists of a feature extractor (ϕ) that learns representations from chest X-ray images, followed by a classifier (ψ) that maps these representations to disease labels. The invariant loss function (LINV) is calculated using features from grouped populations, promoting similarity in representations across demographic boundaries. The architecture operates in a shared weight scenario leveraging backbones such as ResNet, DenseNet, and EfficientNet.	The approach introduces observational grouping as a key mechanism for enforcing invariance in learned representations, allowing models to generalize better across different demographics. This enhances the robustness of the models against biases inherent in the data, which has historically hindered diagnostic validity in AI-driven medical imaging.	The framework can assist radiologists in disease classification tasks by providing more reliable and equitable AI support regardless of patient demographics, thus aiming to improve diagnostic accuracy and reduce disparities in healthcare.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c5/Shield_of_Imperial_College_London.svg/330px-Shield_of_Imperial_College_London.svg.png	2025-06-26 04:00:00+00	2025-06-26 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.20582", "title": "CausalXray"}]	{"Imperial College London"}
d32f9b01-cb79-454f-9c22-bcb08ff4b34b	E-ComSent AI	Enhance the understanding of customer sentiment in real-time to drive strategic decision-making for e-commerce businesses through an AI-driven sentiment analysis system.	E-commerce platforms are overwhelmed by the volume of customer feedback, which varies in context, complexity, and modality. Traditional sentiment analysis methods lack the ability to accurately capture nuanced customer sentiments in a scalable and actionable manner, resulting in missed insights and slow response times.	Real-time sentiment analysis of multi-channel customer feedback (product reviews, social media interactions, customer service communications) for various e-commerce platforms. Enables businesses to derive actionable insights and improve customer satisfaction and operational efficiency.	["E-commerce platforms","Retail businesses","Customer service teams","Marketing departments"]	The system collects and preprocesses customer feedback from multiple sources, including product reviews and social media. It utilizes a hybrid model incorporating fine-tuned transformer architectures for sentiment classification, alongside domain-specific language models. Real-time insights are generated through a multi-layer architecture that includes data ingestion, analysis, and automated reporting of sentiment trends and actionable insights.	Multi-layer architecture comprising: 1) Data Collection and Preprocessing Layer (real-time ingestion, multi-source integration, text normalization). 2) Analysis and Classification Layer (hybrid models with fine-tuned BERT and domain-specific classifiers). 3) Insights Generation Layer (real-time analytics, automated report generation, alert system for sentiment spikes).	The integration of advanced NLP techniques for context-aware sentiment analysis, enabling multi-aspect sentiment detection, and providing real-time actionable insights. This system also prioritizes interpretability, allowing businesses to understand the reasoning behind sentiment classifications and improving response strategies.	E-commerce platforms utilizing the system can improve customer satisfaction by proactively addressing negative sentiments, increasing conversion rates through targeted engagement, and optimizing product offerings based on identified trends in customer feedback.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/b/bb/Carnegie_Mellon_University_seal.svg/300px-Carnegie_Mellon_University_seal.svg.png	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2504.08738", "title": "E-ComSent AI"}]	{"Carnegie Mellon University","University of California, Santa Cruz"}
291e59c3-40fc-4eaa-a0f8-2d29942325f9	Regret-Aware Skill Discovery (RSD)	Enhance the efficiency and diversity of skill discovery in reinforcement learning through a regret-aware optimization framework that balances skill exploration and policy strength.	Existing methods of skill discovery in reinforcement learning suffer from inefficiencies and fail to adaptively explore skills based on their learning status, leading to wasted computational resources and missed opportunities for better skill acquisition. This creates bottlenecks in high-dimensional environments where skills are harder to master.	Unsupervised skill discovery applicable to a wide range of environments in reinforcement learning, particularly those with high-dimensional state spaces and complex task requirements. Optimization of skill learning strategies to increase both efficiency and diversity without reliance on explicit rewards.	["AI researchers","Data scientists","Roboticists","Game developers","Companies developing intelligence systems"]	The RSD framework operates through two interleaved policies: the agent policy learns to minimize regret associated with selected skills, while the skill generator policy focuses on maximizing regret to encourage exploration of less mastered skills. The framework uses regret signals to adaptively sample skills that are under-explored, allowing the agent to prioritize learning of essential yet challenging capabilities.	1. Agent Policy Module: Minimizes regret by optimizing the actions taken for a set of skills drawn from the skill generator. 2. Skill Generator Module: Generates new skill vectors based on regret values of previously explored skills, aimed at producing under-converged skills. 3. Bounded Representation Learning: Ensures stability of the skill representations within the optimization process, enhancing the adaptability to diverse environments.	The introduction of regret-aware optimization as an approach to balance skill discovery and reinforcement learning, allowing for dynamic and efficient exploration. The use of a population of skill generators enables continual skill adaptation and diversity, preventing common pitfalls of skill degeneration. The integration of bounded representation contributes to improved learning and stability across various environments.	Unsupervised skill discovery in robotics, enhancing robotic capabilities to adapt to various tasks without predefined goals. Efficient exploration of skill sets leads to faster and more effective training in real-world applications such as robotic manipulation and autonomous navigation.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/b/b9/NUS_coat_of_arms.svg/260px-NUS_coat_of_arms.svg.png	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.21044", "title": "Regret-Aware Skill Discovery (RSD)"}]	{"The Hong Kong University of Science and Technology","Shanghai AI Lab","National Natural Science Foundation of China"}
6eb468cd-07bb-4ca1-a1c6-6eac05f7cbab	Video-X 2L	To enhance long-video understanding by utilizing an innovative bi-level key-value (KV) compression and selective reloading mechanism while significantly reducing computational costs.	Existing multi-modal large language models struggle to efficiently process long videos due to prohibitive memory and computational demands, resulting in loss of critical fine-grained information during KV compression.	Enable cost-effective processing of long videos by using adaptive KV compression techniques to preserve essential information for various understanding tasks without extensive training.	["Film production companies","Streaming services","Content creators","AI researchers in multimodal processing"]	Video-X 2L operates by performing bi-level KV compression on input video data, generating two types of KVs: low-compression KVs (L-KVs) that retain fine details and high-compression KVs (H-KVs) that provide abstract representations. During the decoding, it selectively reloads the L-KVs for critical video sections while using H-KVs for less important areas, allowing task-specific information to be utilized effectively.	The system consists of a video tokenizer followed by a multi-modal large language model. The video is segmented into chunks, and during pre-filling, both L-KVs and H-KVs are generated. The KV cache is managed efficiently, enabling selective reloading based on task relevance during the decoding stage.	The key innovations include the bi-level KV compression mechanism that differentiates between essential and non-essential video data and the selective KV reloading method that dynamically loads KVs based on importance, facilitating better resource utilization and reducing information loss.	This framework is applicable in scenarios such as film analysis, video summarization, and real-time object tracking, enhancing the ability to derive insights from long-form video content.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/a/af/BUPT_LOGO.png	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.21184", "title": "Video-X 2L"}]	{"Beijing Academy of Artificial Intelligence","Shanghai Jiao Tong University","University of Trento","Hong Kong Polytechnic University","Institute of Automation, CAS, Beijing"}
226aac00-8fb8-4b60-8692-4939e632866a	ScalaBL	Enhance the reliability of large language models (LLMs) by providing efficient Bayesian uncertainty quantification using scalable low-rank adaptation mechanisms.	Large language models often produce incorrect information (hallucinations) and are typically not well-calibrated, which poses risks in critical applications like healthcare and autonomous systems. Existing methods for Bayesian adaptation are often not scalable, requiring too many additional parameters and computational resources.	Implementation of scalable Bayesian low-rank adaptation for large language models to improve uncertainty quantification without significantly increasing memory usage or computational overhead.	["AI researchers","Machine learning engineers","Software developers","Healthcare professionals","Autonomous system designers"]	ScalaBL performs Bayesian inference within a low-dimensional subspace of model weights, using low-rank adaptation parameters to project samples back into the full weight space efficiently. It uses stochastic variational inference to train the model with significantly fewer parameters compared to previous Bayesian approaches.	The system consists of: 1. Input Layer: Receives data to train the LLM. 2. Low-Rank Adaptation Layers: Implements the LoRA technique to minimize the number of parameters updated. 3. Stochastic Variational Inference Layer: Learns variational parameters for the low-dimensional subspace representation. 4. Bayesian Model Averaging Module: Combines the outputs from multiple sampled weights during inference to provide uncertainty estimates.	Employs a unique low-dimensional subspace for Bayesian inference within LLMs that significantly decreases the number of additional parameters required for training. This approach allows the model to scale effectively while maintaining competitive performance in uncertainty metrics.	Certified AI applications needing reliable output, such as in healthcare diagnostics, accident prevention in autonomous vehicles, and legal document analysis, where correct information is critical.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/b/b9/NUS_coat_of_arms.svg/260px-NUS_coat_of_arms.svg.png	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	[{"url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.21408", "title": "ScalaBL"}]	{"SRI International","Neuro-Symbolic Computing and Intelligence Research Group","University Collaborators"}
a236e1a3-466f-4c83-a5f0-726bffb1da3c	skLEP Benchmark	To provide a standardized evaluation benchmark for Slovak natural language understanding (NLU) tasks, fostering the development and assessment of language models tailored for Slovak.	The lack of a comprehensive benchmark for evaluating Slovak NLU models hinders progress and comparison against established multilingual models. Most existing benchmarks focus primarily on high-resource languages, neglecting Slovak, a mid-resource language.	Nine tasks covering token-level, sentence-pair, and document-level challenges for Slovak NLU. This includes datasets for POS tagging, Named Entity Recognition, sentiment analysis, hate speech classification, natural language inference, and question answering.	["NLP researchers","AI developers","Academic institutions","Language model developers"]	The benchmark uses curated and translated datasets across various tasks. Researchers can fine-tune existing language models on skLEP tasks using the provided open-source toolkit integrated with HuggingFace. Evaluation is facilitated through a public leaderboard.	The skLEP toolkit leverages existing models, integrates datasets for evaluation, provides metrics for performance assessment, and hosts a leaderboard for comparing model performance. It supports various formats for model input and output compatibility.	The creation of the first comprehensive Slovak-specific benchmark to systematically evaluate and compare language models. It includes diverse NLU tasks tailored to the nuances of the Slovak language, promoting further research.	Evaluation of Slovak NLU models in academic research, facilitating improved training processes and performance benchmarks against multilingual models, as well as aiding the development of Slovak-specific applications in AI.	https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/Logo_of_the_Technical_University_of_Munich.svg/360px-Logo_of_the_Technical_University_of_Munich.svg.png	2025-06-27 04:00:00+00	2025-0