40ffa887-d6d6-47e6-bdea-3d9162a54725	QuantumUnitarySynthesizer	To develop a scalable quantum neural network that approximates any unitary operator using the Standard Recursive Block Basis (SRBB) for efficient quantum circuit synthesis.	Existing quantum circuit synthesis methods often require significant time and resources due to the complexity of approximating unitary operations, especially as the number of qubits increases. There is a need for more efficient algorithms that can reduce the number of gates, specifically CNOT gates, while maintaining high fidelity in the approximation of unitary operators.	Approximation of unitary operators for quantum circuits using a quantum neural network framework. Focus on scalable synthesis algorithms that minimize the number of CNOT gates while ensuring accurate representation of complex multi-qubit systems.	["Quantum computing researchers","Quantum software developers","Academic institutions","Tech companies exploring quantum technologies"]	The system uses a quantum neural network (QNN) to approximate unitary operators by employing a quantum circuit comprised of parameterized gates represented by the Standard Recursive Block Basis (SRBB). The QNN is trained using classical optimization techniques to minimize the error in approximating the target unitary, leveraging metrics such as Frobenius norm, trace distance, or fidelity. This framework allows for the scalable design and simplification of quantum circuits, particularly reducing the number of required CNOT gates.	The architecture consists of an input layer that encodes classical data into quantum states, followed by layers that implement the quantum operations defined by the SRBB. The main components include the Z-factor for diagonal contributions, the Ψ-factor for even contributions, and the Φ-factor for odd contributions. Each of these factors is optimized to utilize simplified CNOT gates wherever possible, leveraging properties of Lie algebra and permutation group theory.